Well, thanks for having me.

00:00:38.282 --> 00:00:40.740
CINDY HALVORSEN: So for those
of us who have maybe not seen

00:00:40.740 --> 00:00:42.490
the show and just
pretend to see the show,

00:00:42.490 --> 00:00:45.450
can you do a quick recap
of how the show works?

00:00:45.450 --> 00:00:48.165
PHIL KEOGHAN: So the show's now
been going 17 years, for those

00:00:48.165 --> 00:00:49.290
of you who haven't seen it.

00:00:49.290 --> 00:00:53.580
And 29 seasons, we just went
to air with the 29th season.

00:00:53.580 --> 00:00:55.620
And essentially, the
idea is that normally we

00:00:55.620 --> 00:01:00.300
have 11 teams of two in
preexisting relationships--

00:01:00.300 --> 00:01:01.950
grandparents, best
friends, husband

00:01:01.950 --> 00:01:05.160
and wife, engaged
couples, brother/sister.

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:06.600
Whatever that
combination is there

00:01:06.600 --> 00:01:08.433
in a preexisting
relationship, and then they

00:01:08.433 --> 00:01:11.841
race around the world
following a series of clues

00:01:11.841 --> 00:01:12.840
from country to country.

00:01:12.840 --> 00:01:14.714
The slower races get
eliminated along the way

00:01:14.714 --> 00:01:17.590
until we end up with the fastest
three, fastest three teams.

00:01:17.590 --> 00:01:18.370
CINDY HALVORSEN: Or
the luckiest three.

00:01:18.370 --> 00:01:20.078
PHIL KEOGHAN: Or
sometimes we've actually

00:01:20.078 --> 00:01:22.320
had four teams run
in the last leg.

00:01:22.320 --> 00:01:25.200
And then they race to the finish
line to win that $1 million

00:01:25.200 --> 00:01:25.830
prize.

00:01:25.830 --> 00:01:29.040
This season we just
changed things up to--

00:01:29.040 --> 00:01:30.660
that's just to mess
up my explanation

00:01:30.660 --> 00:01:32.040
about how this all works.

00:01:32.040 --> 00:01:34.590
Normally it's 11 teams of two
people who know each other.

00:01:34.590 --> 00:01:36.030
This season what
we decided to do

00:01:36.030 --> 00:01:40.050
was take 22 complete
strangers and pair them up

00:01:40.050 --> 00:01:41.730
at the starting line
so they literally

00:01:41.730 --> 00:01:43.200
didn't know each other's names.

00:01:43.200 --> 00:01:45.300
And that's proved to be
a little interesting.

00:01:45.300 --> 00:01:46.920
You've seen the season so far?

00:01:46.920 --> 00:01:47.550
CINDY HALVORSEN: Of course!

00:01:47.550 --> 00:01:49.100
PHIL KEOGHAN: Well, no,
I just wanted to check.

00:01:49.100 --> 00:01:51.390
I thought maybe after you won,
you thought, all right, we won,

00:01:51.390 --> 00:01:51.930
we're out of here.

00:01:51.930 --> 00:01:53.340
We're going to watch
something else.

00:01:53.340 --> 00:01:54.830
Now it's "The Voice" we're
going to watch or something

00:01:54.830 --> 00:01:55.380
like that.

00:01:55.380 --> 00:01:56.510
CINDY HALVORSEN: We
do watch that too.

00:01:56.510 --> 00:01:57.340
PHIL KEOGHAN: Oh, you do?

00:01:57.340 --> 00:01:57.560
That's good.

00:01:57.560 --> 00:01:59.643
CINDY HALVORSEN: How did
the dynamics of strangers

00:01:59.643 --> 00:02:02.940
being on "The Race" together
change the storytelling

00:02:02.940 --> 00:02:03.690
process?

00:02:03.690 --> 00:02:05.260
PHIL KEOGHAN: Well, you know--

00:02:05.260 --> 00:02:06.540
let's put that down there.

00:02:06.540 --> 00:02:11.166
Normally, when you're in an
existing relationship, if you--

00:02:11.166 --> 00:02:12.540
there's sort of
no filter, right,

00:02:12.540 --> 00:02:15.630
when you're with somebody
in an existing relationship.

00:02:15.630 --> 00:02:19.212
And sometimes people just--

00:02:19.212 --> 00:02:21.420
they bicker at each other,
let's be honest, you know.

00:02:21.420 --> 00:02:23.841
And sometimes that
makes for good TV.

00:02:23.841 --> 00:02:25.590
And sometimes you're
more polite to people

00:02:25.590 --> 00:02:29.000
that you might meet as a
stranger in a supermarket

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:30.880
than you are
sometimes to somebody

00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:32.580
you're apparently meant to love.

00:02:32.580 --> 00:02:35.400
And so at the starting
line, everybody

00:02:35.400 --> 00:02:37.290
was very polite to
each other because they

00:02:37.290 --> 00:02:38.370
didn't know each
other's names, they

00:02:38.370 --> 00:02:39.390
didn't know where
they came from.

00:02:39.390 --> 00:02:41.370
And suddenly they found
themselves paired up

00:02:41.370 --> 00:02:43.230
with a complete stranger.

00:02:43.230 --> 00:02:44.850
And one of the first
things-- after I

00:02:44.850 --> 00:02:46.630
said go, one of the first
things that happened was it's

00:02:46.630 --> 00:02:47.790
like, oh, hi, I'm Phil.

00:02:47.790 --> 00:02:49.350
What's your name,
and where do you

00:02:49.350 --> 00:02:51.790
come from, and all
that sort of stuff?

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:55.490
But the show is shot
12 shows in 21 days.

00:02:55.490 --> 00:02:57.500
And it's a pressure
cooker, as you know.

00:02:57.500 --> 00:03:01.160
And so it took about
80 hours before it

00:03:01.160 --> 00:03:04.190
went from being polite to
strangers or the stranger

00:03:04.190 --> 00:03:07.550
that you were with to no filter.

00:03:07.550 --> 00:03:10.220
Listen, dude.

00:03:10.220 --> 00:03:11.030
This is a team.

00:03:11.030 --> 00:03:13.070
I don't know how you
operate ordinarily,

00:03:13.070 --> 00:03:15.530
but I will not be
spoken to like that.

00:03:15.530 --> 00:03:18.500
You will pull your head in, and
I'm as much a part of this team

00:03:18.500 --> 00:03:20.982
as you are, and so we
need to work together.

00:03:20.982 --> 00:03:22.940
And some of the people
that have been paired up

00:03:22.940 --> 00:03:25.700
are people that you would
just normally not-- like,

00:03:25.700 --> 00:03:28.640
they would not normally choose
to be with a person like that.

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:30.620
This is like the
unwanted relative

00:03:30.620 --> 00:03:32.700
that you have to
have at Thanksgiving

00:03:32.700 --> 00:03:34.400
who says all those
obnoxious things

00:03:34.400 --> 00:03:35.962
and spills food all
over themselves.

00:03:35.962 --> 00:03:38.420
And the only reason that you
have to get together with them

00:03:38.420 --> 00:03:40.420
is because they're family
and it's Thanksgiving.

00:03:40.420 --> 00:03:42.620
So some of the pairings work.

00:03:42.620 --> 00:03:44.370
Some of the pairings don't work.

00:03:44.370 --> 00:03:46.870
And the end result is we
end up with a great show.

00:03:46.870 --> 00:03:48.120
CINDY HALVORSEN: That's great.

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:49.040
That's--

00:03:49.040 --> 00:03:51.080
PHIL KEOGHAN: Makes
for entertaining TV.

00:03:51.080 --> 00:03:52.910
CINDY HALVORSEN: So
over the 29 seasons

00:03:52.910 --> 00:03:56.594
you've raced a
million 68,000 miles.

00:03:56.594 --> 00:03:58.010
PHIL KEOGHAN: I
did not know that.

00:03:58.010 --> 00:03:59.610
CINDY HALVORSEN: Yeah, I just
did the math for you today.

00:03:59.610 --> 00:04:00.952
PHIL KEOGHAN: Wow, I love that.

00:04:00.952 --> 00:04:03.410
CINDY HALVORSEN: So Google Maps
obviously covers the world.

00:04:03.410 --> 00:04:07.106
How do you think Google Maps
plays into "The Amazing Race"?

00:04:07.106 --> 00:04:08.480
PHIL KEOGHAN:
Well, Google Maps--

00:04:08.480 --> 00:04:10.417
I mean, I'm a huge, huge fan.

00:04:10.417 --> 00:04:11.750
I have a great story about that.

00:04:11.750 --> 00:04:14.900
When we talk about my film and
how I used Google in general,

00:04:14.900 --> 00:04:16.640
just the technology.

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:18.488
But think about
how much technology

00:04:18.488 --> 00:04:20.779
has changed since "The Amazing
Race" first went to air.

00:04:20.779 --> 00:04:23.510
You know, we had our
first show in 2001.

00:04:23.510 --> 00:04:28.580
And you could travel the
world and you could hide away

00:04:28.580 --> 00:04:30.890
in countries and people
wouldn't know where you were.

00:04:30.890 --> 00:04:33.200
And now people are
like live broadcasting

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:35.300
us running through the airport.

00:04:35.300 --> 00:04:37.650
And that's just crazy, right?

00:04:37.650 --> 00:04:40.670
I mean, it's like people
have their own broadcasting

00:04:40.670 --> 00:04:42.620
capabilities.

00:04:42.620 --> 00:04:44.870
And people can
obviously use Google.

00:04:44.870 --> 00:04:46.680
If they get access
to a computer,

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:49.090
they can look up certain things.

00:04:49.090 --> 00:04:51.710
And I do believe that that
might have been something

00:04:51.710 --> 00:04:53.570
you might have
done in your time,

00:04:53.570 --> 00:04:54.890
look up a few things in Google?

00:04:54.890 --> 00:04:56.181
CINDY HALVORSEN: Yes, actually.

00:04:56.181 --> 00:04:57.216
PHIL KEOGHAN: Yeah?

00:04:57.216 --> 00:04:58.464
Tell the story.

00:04:58.464 --> 00:05:00.630
CINDY HALVORSEN: So we have
a few points in our race

00:05:00.630 --> 00:05:03.088
where we definitely used Google
Maps to get us from point A

00:05:03.088 --> 00:05:05.495
to point B. The one
time we didn't, we

00:05:05.495 --> 00:05:07.280
used this random Dutch web site.

00:05:07.280 --> 00:05:10.370
We got super lost,
and we lost the cars.

00:05:10.370 --> 00:05:12.080
We went from first
place to third place

00:05:12.080 --> 00:05:13.370
and lost those cars.

00:05:13.370 --> 00:05:15.500
Bummer.

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:17.750
But it actually helped
us in the very final leg

00:05:17.750 --> 00:05:19.070
that you saw here.

00:05:19.070 --> 00:05:22.180
This is-- we raced
six years ago.

00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:22.680
The four--

00:05:22.680 --> 00:05:23.660
PHIL KEOGHAN: Has
it been that long?

00:05:23.660 --> 00:05:24.620
CINDY HALVORSEN: Yeah,
it was that long.

00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:26.410
PHIL KEOGHAN: And you've had
two children since then, right?

00:05:26.410 --> 00:05:27.360
CINDY HALVORSEN: Yeah.

00:05:27.360 --> 00:05:27.800
We have had two.

00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:28.841
PHIL KEOGHAN: Time flies.

00:05:28.841 --> 00:05:29.842
CINDY HALVORSEN: I know.

00:05:29.842 --> 00:05:32.174
PHIL KEOGHAN: I was in my 30s
when we started this show.

00:05:32.174 --> 00:05:32.990
Now-- now I'm--

00:05:32.990 --> 00:05:33.630
CINDY HALVORSEN: Now you're 35.

00:05:33.630 --> 00:05:34.750
PHIL KEOGHAN: Now
I'm not in my 30s.

00:05:34.750 --> 00:05:35.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:35.250 --> 00:05:36.935
I'm a little older.

00:05:36.935 --> 00:05:38.070
And you've got two kids.

00:05:38.070 --> 00:05:38.820
How'd that happen?

00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:39.090
CINDY HALVORSEN: I know.

00:05:39.090 --> 00:05:40.970
Yeah, so it was the
age of flip phones.

00:05:40.970 --> 00:05:44.930
And so we texted Google the
clue to the final pit stop,

00:05:44.930 --> 00:05:46.405
and it texted us the answer.

00:05:46.405 --> 00:05:47.030
It was awesome.

00:05:47.030 --> 00:05:47.790
PHIL KEOGHAN: Don't
you love that?

00:05:47.790 --> 00:05:48.090
CINDY HALVORSEN: Yep.

00:05:48.090 --> 00:05:49.647
PHIL KEOGHAN: Yay for Google.

00:05:49.647 --> 00:05:51.230
Is that why you ended
up working here,

00:05:51.230 --> 00:05:52.855
because you figured
you've got to give back?

00:05:52.855 --> 00:05:53.190
Got to give back?

00:05:53.190 --> 00:05:54.260
CINDY HALVORSEN: Yeah.

00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:55.020
I think it helped us win.

00:05:55.020 --> 00:05:56.470
PHIL KEOGHAN: This is your debt?

00:05:56.470 --> 00:05:57.260
It worked out.

00:05:57.260 --> 00:05:58.460
CINDY HALVORSEN: Now I
give my service to Google.

00:05:58.460 --> 00:06:00.043
PHIL KEOGHAN: Yeah,
no, I'm a big fan.

00:06:00.043 --> 00:06:04.010
And in this film that
I shot, I reached

00:06:04.010 --> 00:06:06.830
out to Google and Google
Maps, and hugely helpful.

00:06:06.830 --> 00:06:10.850
I mean, it's just changed the
way that we see the world.

00:06:10.850 --> 00:06:13.490
Because I love maps.

00:06:13.490 --> 00:06:15.090
I really love tactile maps.

00:06:15.090 --> 00:06:17.180
I love putting them up
on the wall and looking.

00:06:17.180 --> 00:06:18.560
But there's
something amazing now

00:06:18.560 --> 00:06:20.900
just about being able to
drop in and really explore

00:06:20.900 --> 00:06:22.780
a place before you get there.

00:06:22.780 --> 00:06:26.170
And it's sort of the trip before
the trip that you can now take.

00:06:26.170 --> 00:06:31.010
Also just writing the
scripts for "Amazing Race,"

00:06:31.010 --> 00:06:35.750
I'm constantly on Google to
look up fascinating facts

00:06:35.750 --> 00:06:37.430
and figures--

00:06:37.430 --> 00:06:40.010
real facts, not false facts--

00:06:40.010 --> 00:06:41.320
to put into the show.

00:06:41.320 --> 00:06:44.030
You know, the audience
love the little facts

00:06:44.030 --> 00:06:45.410
that we give along the way.

00:06:45.410 --> 00:06:47.660
So I'm always looking for
the really interesting ones,

00:06:47.660 --> 00:06:50.510
like how many thousand islands
there are in Indonesia.

00:06:50.510 --> 00:06:52.430
And people are always
surprised by that.

00:06:52.430 --> 00:06:55.010
And fascinating facts
about the deepest lakes

00:06:55.010 --> 00:06:56.990
and all those sort of stuff.

00:06:56.990 --> 00:06:58.050
So I like it.

00:06:58.050 --> 00:06:58.770
CINDY HALVORSEN: That's great.

00:06:58.770 --> 00:06:59.311
That's great.

00:06:59.311 --> 00:07:01.370
So take us actually to
the production room.

00:07:01.370 --> 00:07:03.170
So there's lots of
conversation that

00:07:03.170 --> 00:07:07.310
happens before you plot out the
show and actually go and film.

00:07:07.310 --> 00:07:09.660
Take us to the table where
you're having conversation

00:07:09.660 --> 00:07:11.820
with Bertram, Elise,
whoever else is in the room.

00:07:11.820 --> 00:07:15.860
PHIL KEOGHAN: Well, yeah,
I mean, Bertram and Elise,

00:07:15.860 --> 00:07:18.560
you know, they work
with a fantastic team.

00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:23.990
And Bertram takes the
first hand at sketching out

00:07:23.990 --> 00:07:26.790
where he wants to go.

00:07:26.790 --> 00:07:28.970
And then from there,
everybody supports him

00:07:28.970 --> 00:07:33.320
and looking for great
stories and great ideas.

00:07:33.320 --> 00:07:36.260
Supported by a really
great group of people.

00:07:36.260 --> 00:07:39.320
And what's good about the show
now being on as long as it has,

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:42.080
a lot of people have
come to us inviting us

00:07:42.080 --> 00:07:44.240
to come to their countries too.

00:07:44.240 --> 00:07:45.890
And then ultimately,
CBS is the one

00:07:45.890 --> 00:07:49.310
that signs off on
not only where we go

00:07:49.310 --> 00:07:50.660
but who we have on the show.

00:07:50.660 --> 00:07:52.340
So Les Moonves still has--

00:07:52.340 --> 00:07:55.050
Les Moonves, for those of
you who don't know, runs--

00:07:55.050 --> 00:07:58.320
I mean, the guy is
very successful.

00:07:58.320 --> 00:08:01.642
But he really does take
a hand on everybody

00:08:01.642 --> 00:08:02.600
who goes on "The Race."

00:08:02.600 --> 00:08:07.540
And then ultimately CBS signs
off on the route that we go to.

00:08:07.540 --> 00:08:10.025
Do you say "root" or
"rowt" in America?

00:08:10.025 --> 00:08:10.525
"Rowt"?

00:08:10.525 --> 00:08:11.460
CINDY HALVORSEN:
"Tomayto," "tomahto."

00:08:11.460 --> 00:08:12.230
Probably both.

00:08:12.230 --> 00:08:12.350
PHIL KEOGHAN:
"Tomayto," "tomahto."

00:08:12.350 --> 00:08:14.120
What would you say,
"root" or "rowt"?

00:08:14.120 --> 00:08:14.600
AUDIENCE: "Rowt."

00:08:14.600 --> 00:08:15.475
PHIL KEOGHAN: "Rowt."

00:08:15.475 --> 00:08:17.390
So Les Moonves signs
off on the "rowt"--

00:08:17.390 --> 00:08:19.050
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:19.050 --> 00:08:20.180
--that we take.

00:08:20.180 --> 00:08:25.200
And then from there, we've been
to some just incredible places.

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:30.170
And what I love about our show
is, unlike a stage show or so

00:08:30.170 --> 00:08:32.530
many shows that
are on television,

00:08:32.530 --> 00:08:34.580
the background is
always different.

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:37.280
You know, you never
see the same background

00:08:37.280 --> 00:08:39.500
twice on "Amazing Race."

00:08:39.500 --> 00:08:42.450
It's harder, I think,
for other shows,

00:08:42.450 --> 00:08:45.960
whether they're staged
shows like, you know,

00:08:45.960 --> 00:08:47.119
a singing competition show.

00:08:47.119 --> 00:08:49.160
I think it's harder for
them to stay fresh season

00:08:49.160 --> 00:08:51.129
after season just because--

00:08:51.129 --> 00:08:53.420
one of the things-- just
because the stage is the same.

00:08:53.420 --> 00:08:55.711
They can change the lighting
and do a few things there,

00:08:55.711 --> 00:08:59.570
but we have the ability
to really radically change

00:08:59.570 --> 00:09:03.042
the look of the show,
not only by where they go

00:09:03.042 --> 00:09:03.750
but what they do.

00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:05.580
And of course,
like all shows, we

00:09:05.580 --> 00:09:08.050
change the people who
come on every season.

00:09:08.050 --> 00:09:10.950
CINDY HALVORSEN: So let's talk
about the different locations.

00:09:10.950 --> 00:09:13.481
You had mentioned it's like
traveling before you travel,

00:09:13.481 --> 00:09:13.980
right?

00:09:13.980 --> 00:09:14.840
When you're--

00:09:14.840 --> 00:09:16.590
PHIL KEOGHAN: With the
research, you mean?

00:09:16.590 --> 00:09:18.256
CINDY HALVORSEN: Yes,
with the research.

00:09:18.256 --> 00:09:20.130
So talk about in today's
political climate,

00:09:20.130 --> 00:09:22.320
where people maybe don't
feel as comfortable

00:09:22.320 --> 00:09:23.220
traveling the world.

00:09:23.220 --> 00:09:25.890
How does "Amazing Race"
play in that conversation?

00:09:25.890 --> 00:09:28.290
PHIL KEOGHAN: That's a
really good question.

00:09:28.290 --> 00:09:31.020
A lot of people assume
that America is the safest

00:09:31.020 --> 00:09:33.210
country in the world.

00:09:33.210 --> 00:09:34.860
America is a very safe country.

00:09:34.860 --> 00:09:36.990
It's not the safest
country in the world.

00:09:36.990 --> 00:09:40.920
And so then you ask people,
well, where does America rate?

00:09:40.920 --> 00:09:42.870
You guys can Google
it right now.

00:09:42.870 --> 00:09:45.445
Where does America rate in
terms of being the safest

00:09:45.445 --> 00:09:46.320
country in the world?

00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:48.870
And it's way further down
than a lot of people realize.

00:09:48.870 --> 00:09:52.240
Now we'd all agree that
America is a safe country.

00:09:52.240 --> 00:09:54.070
So if America is
as safe as it is--

00:09:54.070 --> 00:09:56.400
and it's not even
in the top 10--

00:09:56.400 --> 00:09:58.410
then, gosh, there's
a lot of safe places

00:09:58.410 --> 00:10:00.400
to travel to in the world.

00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:02.700
The reason that a lot of
people who haven't traveled,

00:10:02.700 --> 00:10:05.400
which is why I
really love stressing

00:10:05.400 --> 00:10:08.900
the importance of travel,
particularly for young people,

00:10:08.900 --> 00:10:10.460
is that their
perception of the world

00:10:10.460 --> 00:10:12.376
is that wherever you go
in the world something

00:10:12.376 --> 00:10:13.670
is going to be going wrong.

00:10:13.670 --> 00:10:15.500
Because when they see
the rest of the world

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:18.470
normally, in network primetime
television or on the news,

00:10:18.470 --> 00:10:21.680
something is going wrong because
of that old news adage, which

00:10:21.680 --> 00:10:23.690
is, if it bleeds, it leads.

00:10:23.690 --> 00:10:26.090
So generally
speaking, if somebody

00:10:26.090 --> 00:10:29.180
sees something
about Spain, they'll

00:10:29.180 --> 00:10:32.780
see when there's been a riot or
there's been some big protest

00:10:32.780 --> 00:10:34.680
or something has gone wrong.

00:10:34.680 --> 00:10:37.670
And so people, if they start
to hear that over and over

00:10:37.670 --> 00:10:39.710
and over and over
again, they just assume,

00:10:39.710 --> 00:10:41.660
why would I want
to get on a plane

00:10:41.660 --> 00:10:45.020
and leave this safe country of
mine, this safe neighborhood,

00:10:45.020 --> 00:10:48.140
this safe state that I
live in and go to a place

00:10:48.140 --> 00:10:49.520
where things are going wrong?

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:51.590
So what we get to
do is to juxtapose

00:10:51.590 --> 00:10:54.559
that with, hey, look at
all these safe places

00:10:54.559 --> 00:10:55.850
you can travel to in the world.

00:10:55.850 --> 00:10:57.500
Look at all these
amazing people.

00:10:57.500 --> 00:10:59.416
Look at all these wonderful
things you can do.

00:10:59.416 --> 00:11:02.750
So we really are the antithesis
of what the news is doing.

00:11:02.750 --> 00:11:04.850
We are celebrating
what's right in the world

00:11:04.850 --> 00:11:07.850
as opposed to amplifying
and playing up

00:11:07.850 --> 00:11:11.490
and selling what's wrong.

00:11:11.490 --> 00:11:13.160
So I think it is
hugely important.

00:11:13.160 --> 00:11:15.430
And you know, just seeing
different cultures,

00:11:15.430 --> 00:11:19.150
seeing the ways that different
people live around the world,

00:11:19.150 --> 00:11:21.650
it's important for all of us
to be exposed to that, I think.

00:11:21.650 --> 00:11:24.680
And so our show,
network primetime show,

00:11:24.680 --> 00:11:26.990
millions of people,
literally, watching.

00:11:26.990 --> 00:11:29.049
You know, appointment viewing.

00:11:29.049 --> 00:11:31.340
I love being involved in
something that, again, there's

00:11:31.340 --> 00:11:34.070
enough of the celebration
of what's wrong.

00:11:34.070 --> 00:11:36.325
I love that our show really
does focus on, all right,

00:11:36.325 --> 00:11:38.200
we're going to show you
something really cool

00:11:38.200 --> 00:11:39.765
that maybe you
haven't seen before.

00:11:39.765 --> 00:11:41.015
CINDY HALVORSEN: That's great.

00:11:41.015 --> 00:11:43.080
So similarly, let's talk about--

00:11:43.080 --> 00:11:45.260
at Google, we believe
a diverse team

00:11:45.260 --> 00:11:46.890
can lead to better results.

00:11:46.890 --> 00:11:49.490
Let's talk about the diversity
that you've shown on "The Race"

00:11:49.490 --> 00:11:54.740
in terms of the cast and what
qualities of these diverse cast

00:11:54.740 --> 00:11:56.120
members make a better team.

00:11:56.120 --> 00:11:57.710
PHIL KEOGHAN: Well,
diversity is key.

00:11:57.710 --> 00:11:59.300
And I mean, I come
from New Zealand.

00:11:59.300 --> 00:12:02.840
One of the reasons I came to
America is I saw it as a place

00:12:02.840 --> 00:12:04.890
where you could make
anything happen.

00:12:04.890 --> 00:12:08.070
And coming from New
Zealand and growing up,

00:12:08.070 --> 00:12:12.590
what you read about America
is it's always sold and taught

00:12:12.590 --> 00:12:15.200
as the land of opportunity.

00:12:15.200 --> 00:12:17.540
And this is a country
of immigrants.

00:12:17.540 --> 00:12:19.370
This is a country
where people came

00:12:19.370 --> 00:12:24.770
from all corners of the world to
find a better life in America.

00:12:24.770 --> 00:12:26.420
And that's why I
like living here.

00:12:26.420 --> 00:12:28.290
I love my country, New Zealand.

00:12:28.290 --> 00:12:30.590
But the opportunities
that are here far

00:12:30.590 --> 00:12:34.330
exceed what is available
in New Zealand.

00:12:34.330 --> 00:12:38.660
And so I also feel like
in America there's always

00:12:38.660 --> 00:12:43.040
been a celebration of success.

00:12:43.040 --> 00:12:48.320
And that success has come
from such a myriad of people.

00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:51.860
We have prided ourselves in
always casting a diverse cast

00:12:51.860 --> 00:12:56.120
to represent the plethora
of the American people.

00:12:56.120 --> 00:12:59.000
If you remember the
Guidos in season 1

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.250
where they were openly
affectionate with each other

00:13:01.250 --> 00:13:02.630
as a gay couple.

00:13:02.630 --> 00:13:03.880
That was in 2001.

00:13:03.880 --> 00:13:05.480
It was kind of radical.

00:13:05.480 --> 00:13:08.120
People weren't that comfortable
with seeing that sort of thing

00:13:08.120 --> 00:13:09.900
on television.

00:13:09.900 --> 00:13:13.670
So we are trying to perpetuate
the idea of acceptance

00:13:13.670 --> 00:13:16.460
and difference and
that with difference

00:13:16.460 --> 00:13:19.070
comes a more
interesting country.

00:13:19.070 --> 00:13:22.760
And so if ever there was a
time to celebrate difference

00:13:22.760 --> 00:13:24.860
and to focus on the fact
that difference is good

00:13:24.860 --> 00:13:27.020
and diversity is
good, it's right now.

00:13:27.020 --> 00:13:29.930
Because if we
polarize-- if we start

00:13:29.930 --> 00:13:32.980
getting more and more
polarized, we will get division.

00:13:32.980 --> 00:13:35.450
There's misunderstanding
that comes from all of that.

00:13:35.450 --> 00:13:39.375
So I obviously-- I don't
know this for a fact,

00:13:39.375 --> 00:13:41.000
and I don't want to
give a false fact--

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:44.460
but I would venture
to say that--

00:13:44.460 --> 00:13:45.500
nobody wants to do that.

00:13:45.500 --> 00:13:48.189
I don't want to do fake
news or anything like that.

00:13:48.189 --> 00:13:49.730
But I would venture
to say that we've

00:13:49.730 --> 00:13:52.850
had probably the most diverse
cast of any reality show.

00:13:52.850 --> 00:13:56.090
If you think about it, even if
you look at all the competition

00:13:56.090 --> 00:13:58.970
shows, they're all
singers who are diverse.

00:13:58.970 --> 00:14:01.310
They're all designers
who are diverse.

00:14:01.310 --> 00:14:04.250
They all do one particular
thing and they're diverse.

00:14:04.250 --> 00:14:05.810
They dance and they're diverse.

00:14:05.810 --> 00:14:07.730
Or they're celebrities
and they dance.

00:14:07.730 --> 00:14:09.100
Or whatever the show is.

00:14:09.100 --> 00:14:12.320
But we have a cast,
particularly this season

00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:15.290
with 22 individuals.

00:14:15.290 --> 00:14:17.960
They are black, they're white,
they're tall, they're short,

00:14:17.960 --> 00:14:20.150
they're fit, they're unfit.

00:14:20.150 --> 00:14:22.736
Rich, poor, Democrats,
Republicans.

00:14:22.736 --> 00:14:24.110
CINDY HALVORSEN:
Limbs, no limbs.

00:14:24.110 --> 00:14:25.380
PHIL KEOGHAN: Limbs-- exactly.

00:14:25.380 --> 00:14:27.820
Some people-- we've had amputee.

00:14:27.820 --> 00:14:31.970
Remember we had Sarah, who's
an unbelievable athlete.

00:14:31.970 --> 00:14:34.140
We had Luke, who was deaf.

00:14:34.140 --> 00:14:38.180
We've tried to have as much
diversity as we possibly can.

00:14:38.180 --> 00:14:39.740
At the end of the
day, we're still

00:14:39.740 --> 00:14:40.950
casting interesting people.

00:14:40.950 --> 00:14:42.620
We have to have
interesting people.

00:14:42.620 --> 00:14:44.990
But I feel like the net
that we can throw out

00:14:44.990 --> 00:14:49.110
to find interesting people
is a much bigger net than,

00:14:49.110 --> 00:14:51.410
oh, we're going to throw
a net out but, by the way,

00:14:51.410 --> 00:14:52.797
you all have to
sing really well.

00:14:52.797 --> 00:14:54.380
You know, we're not
about that at all.

00:14:54.380 --> 00:14:57.171
These people come in and, trust
me, some of them cannot sing.

00:14:57.171 --> 00:14:57.920
They cannot dance.

00:14:57.920 --> 00:14:58.660
CINDY HALVORSEN: That's me.

00:14:58.660 --> 00:14:59.120
And me.

00:14:59.120 --> 00:15:00.000
PHIL KEOGHAN: They come into it.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:00.950
And do you remember Dandrew?

00:15:00.950 --> 00:15:02.910
Do you remember that
when they were in Russia

00:15:02.910 --> 00:15:04.210
and he was trying to march?

00:15:04.210 --> 00:15:06.835
For any of you who remember that
season in Russia, and he was--

00:15:06.835 --> 00:15:08.960
[COUGHING] excuse
me-- trying to march

00:15:08.960 --> 00:15:10.214
and he just could not do it.

00:15:10.214 --> 00:15:11.630
And you know people
who don't know

00:15:11.630 --> 00:15:13.580
that they don't have rhythm.

00:15:13.580 --> 00:15:17.780
They're worse than anything
because they are adamant that

00:15:17.780 --> 00:15:20.550
they're in step, but they're--
no, oh, it was hysterical.

00:15:20.550 --> 00:15:24.294
So diversity is a
big part of, I think,

00:15:24.294 --> 00:15:25.460
what has made our show work.

00:15:25.460 --> 00:15:29.620
Because people at home identify
with somebody on the cast.

00:15:29.620 --> 00:15:31.500
There's somebody there
that is their uncle

00:15:31.500 --> 00:15:33.380
or they feel like
they see themselves

00:15:33.380 --> 00:15:35.879
emulated in that person so.

00:15:35.879 --> 00:15:36.920
CINDY HALVORSEN: Awesome.

00:15:36.920 --> 00:15:39.980
Well, you've also
had many YouTubers.

00:15:39.980 --> 00:15:44.020
We have one here today who's
going to be visiting us.

00:15:44.020 --> 00:15:46.069
You've had many
YouTubers on the cast.

00:15:46.069 --> 00:15:48.110
PHIL KEOGHAN: Well, we
had a season of YouTubers.

00:15:48.110 --> 00:15:48.320
CINDY HALVORSEN: Yes.

00:15:48.320 --> 00:15:49.153
PHIL KEOGHAN: Right?

00:15:49.153 --> 00:15:51.950
And what we were
trying to do there was,

00:15:51.950 --> 00:15:56.360
again, just embrace the fact
that the world has changed

00:15:56.360 --> 00:15:59.540
so much, the way that
people communicate,

00:15:59.540 --> 00:16:02.450
the fact that Tyler Oakley
can reach as many people as he

00:16:02.450 --> 00:16:03.440
had or--

00:16:03.440 --> 00:16:08.060
the idea that anybody
now can find a platform

00:16:08.060 --> 00:16:09.980
to be able to share
something that they do.

00:16:09.980 --> 00:16:13.010
Maybe they're amazing at
embroidery and they have--

00:16:13.010 --> 00:16:16.914
there's a guy online
who ties flies.

00:16:16.914 --> 00:16:18.830
And I think he has, like,
a million followers.

00:16:18.830 --> 00:16:21.290
And he literally sits
and tells people how--

00:16:21.290 --> 00:16:23.840
flies that you make for
fishing, fly fishing?

00:16:23.840 --> 00:16:25.820
He literally is-- his--

00:16:25.820 --> 00:16:26.960
yeah, I guess I didn't--

00:16:26.960 --> 00:16:27.820
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:27.820 --> 00:16:29.580
CINDY HALVORSEN: I thought you
were talking about flies flies.

00:16:29.580 --> 00:16:30.190
PHIL KEOGHAN: He ties flies.

00:16:30.190 --> 00:16:31.100
Oh, yeah, no, no.

00:16:31.100 --> 00:16:32.140
Flies flies.

00:16:32.140 --> 00:16:35.050
Although some guys do use
live flies on their flies.

00:16:35.050 --> 00:16:36.657
Did you know that?

00:16:36.657 --> 00:16:37.240
No, it's true.

00:16:37.240 --> 00:16:37.830
CINDY HALVORSEN: I know
nothing about fishing.

00:16:37.830 --> 00:16:40.500
PHIL KEOGHAN: No, they've tied
live flies on their flies.

00:16:40.500 --> 00:16:41.500
Because they look like--

00:16:41.500 --> 00:16:42.670
I mean, because they
are flies, and then

00:16:42.670 --> 00:16:44.045
they put it on
the hook, and then

00:16:44.045 --> 00:16:46.420
the fish sees the
real fly, and then

00:16:46.420 --> 00:16:47.870
the fish eats that live fly.

00:16:47.870 --> 00:16:50.050
And the live fly is on a fly.

00:16:50.050 --> 00:16:52.015
And then that fly gets the fish.

00:16:52.015 --> 00:16:53.140
CINDY HALVORSEN: Excellent.

00:16:53.140 --> 00:16:54.640
PHIL KEOGHAN: You
think I'm kidding.

00:16:54.640 --> 00:16:55.260
I'm not.

00:16:55.260 --> 00:16:55.500
Anyway--

00:16:55.500 --> 00:16:56.180
CINDY HALVORSEN: I
kind of follow you.

00:16:56.180 --> 00:16:59.140
PHIL KEOGHAN: I'm just saying
that anybody can do anything,

00:16:59.140 --> 00:17:01.090
and they can be online.

00:17:01.090 --> 00:17:02.800
And so we wanted
to embrace that.

00:17:02.800 --> 00:17:06.160
And so we tried it,
and it was interesting.

00:17:06.160 --> 00:17:08.710
I think, you know, we
also thought, well,

00:17:08.710 --> 00:17:12.280
maybe those people who follow
those particular people

00:17:12.280 --> 00:17:13.960
online will come
and sample our show

00:17:13.960 --> 00:17:16.624
and get a look at our show.

00:17:16.624 --> 00:17:18.040
But I think you
have to stay-- you

00:17:18.040 --> 00:17:20.859
have to try to stay current
with the zeitgeist of what's

00:17:20.859 --> 00:17:22.089
going on, right?

00:17:22.089 --> 00:17:25.130
Which is-- I mean, you guys
are doing it every day.

00:17:25.130 --> 00:17:26.410
You guys are--

00:17:26.410 --> 00:17:28.291
I mean, the changes.

00:17:28.291 --> 00:17:30.790
Think of how-- I mean, you were
talking about just six years

00:17:30.790 --> 00:17:32.710
ago with flipout phones and--

00:17:32.710 --> 00:17:33.310
right?

00:17:33.310 --> 00:17:34.226
CINDY HALVORSEN: Yeah.

00:17:34.226 --> 00:17:37.090
PHIL KEOGHAN: I mean, it's
changing all the time.

00:17:37.090 --> 00:17:38.080
I love living in--

00:17:38.080 --> 00:17:39.110
I love technology.

00:17:39.110 --> 00:17:40.910
I love living in the future.

00:17:40.910 --> 00:17:42.640
So I love embracing change.

00:17:42.640 --> 00:17:45.310
And I have a daughter who's
about to graduate college.

00:17:45.310 --> 00:17:48.674
And growing up-- her
growing up in the house,

00:17:48.674 --> 00:17:51.090
it was great because I always
wanted to know, what are you

00:17:51.090 --> 00:17:51.631
listening to?

00:17:51.631 --> 00:17:52.780
What are you watching?

00:17:52.780 --> 00:17:54.640
What are you guys talking about?

00:17:54.640 --> 00:17:57.410
What are the things that you--
you know, when Heelys were in.

00:17:57.410 --> 00:18:00.120
Do you remember Heelys, the
shoes with the little wheels?

00:18:00.120 --> 00:18:02.070
My daughter had those,
and we traveled a lot.

00:18:02.070 --> 00:18:05.780
So she would use those and she
would be zooming all around.

00:18:05.780 --> 00:18:07.906
And she loved traveling
because we'd go to airports

00:18:07.906 --> 00:18:09.988
and there were all these
long, long hallways where

00:18:09.988 --> 00:18:11.850
she could just be like,
you know, launching.

00:18:11.850 --> 00:18:14.936
Especially in Chicago, where
you've got those great long--

00:18:14.936 --> 00:18:16.810
and she used to do all
kinds of crazy things.

00:18:16.810 --> 00:18:20.090
And so then she got me on a
pair and I almost broke my leg.

00:18:20.090 --> 00:18:24.420
And they're hard to
use, if you ever--

00:18:24.420 --> 00:18:27.360
No, I love staying current.

00:18:27.360 --> 00:18:29.840
I think you can't dig
your head in the sand

00:18:29.840 --> 00:18:36.534
and just sort of continually
look at putting VHS

00:18:36.534 --> 00:18:37.700
cassettes into your machine.

00:18:37.700 --> 00:18:39.474
You got to kind of evolve.

00:18:39.474 --> 00:18:40.890
CINDY HALVORSEN:
Yes, that's good.

00:18:40.890 --> 00:18:44.120
Did you know that your
most searched about season

