So they got the
watermelon, put it

00:19:31.570 --> 00:19:34.150
in a little leather pouch
with the big rubber bands,

00:19:34.150 --> 00:19:36.067
and they pulled it back
and pulled it back.

00:19:36.067 --> 00:19:38.400
She's pulling and pulling and
pulling, pulling, pulling.

00:19:38.400 --> 00:19:39.360
And then boom!

00:19:39.360 --> 00:19:40.080
She lets it go.

00:19:40.080 --> 00:19:44.700
And somehow, the watermelon went
out, and the piece of leather

00:19:44.700 --> 00:19:46.830
flipped around the watermelon.

00:19:46.830 --> 00:19:49.590
And then with all
that force, boom!

00:19:49.590 --> 00:19:52.650
And came right back, hit
her right in the chin.

00:19:52.650 --> 00:19:55.590
And you just see her,
like, reel backwards.

00:19:55.590 --> 00:19:59.010
And that video went to
like a million views.

00:19:59.010 --> 00:20:00.290
CINDY HALVORSEN: 11 million.

00:20:00.290 --> 00:20:02.460
PHIL KEOGHAN: Well, in the
day it went to a million.

00:20:02.460 --> 00:20:03.150
It's now 11?

00:20:03.150 --> 00:20:04.300
CINDY HALVORSEN:
It's 11 million.

00:20:04.300 --> 00:20:05.100
PHIL KEOGHAN: OK,
that's substantial.

00:20:05.100 --> 00:20:06.510
CINDY HALVORSEN: The one time
was probably enough for Claire.

00:20:06.510 --> 00:20:07.260
11 million is the internet.

00:20:07.260 --> 00:20:08.070
PHIL KEOGHAN: And
that was an old video.

00:20:08.070 --> 00:20:09.990
Had that happened
today, that would

00:20:09.990 --> 00:20:12.420
be like 100-million-view video.

00:20:12.420 --> 00:20:15.330
But I mean-- and quite
frankly, we were really lucky

00:20:15.330 --> 00:20:16.615
that she didn't get hurt.

00:20:16.615 --> 00:20:17.240
CINDY HALVORSEN: Yes.

00:20:17.240 --> 00:20:19.198
PHIL KEOGHAN: But that's
one of those anomalies

00:20:19.198 --> 00:20:22.490
that you just-- you know, made
for good TV, though, didn't it?

00:20:22.490 --> 00:20:23.450
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:23.450 --> 00:20:24.300
Are you OK?

00:20:24.300 --> 00:20:25.030
OK, great.

00:20:25.030 --> 00:20:26.910
That was great TV.

00:20:26.910 --> 00:20:29.105
Don't do it again.

00:20:29.105 --> 00:20:30.980
CINDY HALVORSEN: Keep
going, keep going, yep.

00:20:30.980 --> 00:20:32.887
But I'm sure she did
not want that hitting

00:20:32.887 --> 00:20:33.970
her face 11 million times.

00:20:33.970 --> 00:20:36.800
The slowmo is the best, if you
go back to YouTube and watch

00:20:36.800 --> 00:20:37.530
the slowmo.

00:20:37.530 --> 00:20:39.030
PHIL KEOGHAN: Oh,
yeah, you're sick.

00:20:39.030 --> 00:20:40.519
You watched that in slow motion.

00:20:40.519 --> 00:20:42.060
CINDY HALVORSEN:
It's so fascinating.

00:20:42.060 --> 00:20:42.520
The watermelon just--

00:20:42.520 --> 00:20:42.885
PHIL KEOGHAN: It is fascinating.

00:20:42.885 --> 00:20:44.180
I did watch it in slowmo too.

00:20:44.180 --> 00:20:46.000
It's like--

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:47.820
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:47.820 --> 00:20:48.737
Yeah.

00:20:48.737 --> 00:20:50.070
CINDY HALVORSEN: That's awesome.

00:20:50.070 --> 00:20:55.050
So the show films over-- each
episode is a couple of days.

00:20:55.050 --> 00:20:58.070
PHIL KEOGHAN: Yeah, so
it's 12 shows in 21 days.

00:20:58.070 --> 00:21:00.730
Which a lot of people don't
realize, is it's nuts.

00:21:00.730 --> 00:21:02.490
I mean, you think about that.

00:21:02.490 --> 00:21:04.570
Right now we're on episode 3.

00:21:04.570 --> 00:21:07.980
So those teams, those strangers
have known each other about 85

00:21:07.980 --> 00:21:10.240
hours.

00:21:10.240 --> 00:21:14.140
And people, because we're
spread out week after week,

00:21:14.140 --> 00:21:17.530
people assume that, you know,
there's all this downtime.

00:21:17.530 --> 00:21:20.170
And I often get people
who say, oh, Phil, you

00:21:20.170 --> 00:21:23.480
must just, like, hang out at
the pool and drink pina coladas.

00:21:23.480 --> 00:21:27.000
And I'm like, dude,
you have no idea.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:30.220
I'm trying to race ahead of
these people who are hell

00:21:30.220 --> 00:21:32.470
bent on racing ahead of me.

00:21:32.470 --> 00:21:34.102
And they're fast.

00:21:34.102 --> 00:21:38.190
You get winners like you
around, it gets challenging.

00:21:38.190 --> 00:21:39.940
CINDY HALVORSEN: So
what is the best thing

00:21:39.940 --> 00:21:42.700
left on the cutting room floor?

00:21:42.700 --> 00:21:46.000
PHIL KEOGHAN: Well, I am going
to tell you this categorically.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:49.600
If there's anything
that is that good,

00:21:49.600 --> 00:21:51.230
there's no way
it's on the floor.

00:21:51.230 --> 00:21:53.780
I mean, that would be
like, oh, yeah, well, it

00:21:53.780 --> 00:21:56.290
was this great scene where the
watermelon came back and hit

00:21:56.290 --> 00:21:57.165
the girl in the face.

00:21:57.165 --> 00:21:58.390
We left it on the floor.

00:21:58.390 --> 00:21:59.350
No, trust me.

00:21:59.350 --> 00:22:00.910
If it's good, it's in the show.

00:22:00.910 --> 00:22:03.340
We will find a way to
put it in if it's good.

00:22:03.340 --> 00:22:05.580
So no.

00:22:05.580 --> 00:22:06.910
Yeah, no.

00:22:06.910 --> 00:22:10.180
We're lucky that we have
so many great moments.

00:22:10.180 --> 00:22:15.700
And it all starts
with great ideas.

00:22:15.700 --> 00:22:19.150
And you know, the great ideas
filter down from the top,

00:22:19.150 --> 00:22:24.730
from Bertram and his
vision of what he wants

00:22:24.730 --> 00:22:27.410
and then other people injecting
great ideas into the show.

00:22:27.410 --> 00:22:31.060
And it's a huge
collaboration, you know,

00:22:31.060 --> 00:22:34.540
because it's one thing to
have an idea for something.

00:22:34.540 --> 00:22:36.910
It's another thing to
execute it, as we all know.

00:22:36.910 --> 00:22:39.460
We've seen so many great
ideas poorly executed.

00:22:39.460 --> 00:22:41.110
"Amazing Race" is
a great idea that's

00:22:41.110 --> 00:22:44.660
been beautifully executed.

00:22:44.660 --> 00:22:49.032
It was originally Elise
Doganieri's idea for a show

00:22:49.032 --> 00:22:50.740
because Bertram
challenged her to come up

00:22:50.740 --> 00:22:52.930
with a good idea for a show.

00:22:52.930 --> 00:22:57.250
And she had been backpacking
in Europe and thought, well--

00:22:57.250 --> 00:22:59.650
and I guess there were a few
sparks with her traveling

00:22:59.650 --> 00:23:02.275
partner, and maybe she felt that
would make for a good TV show.

00:23:02.275 --> 00:23:04.930
And so it started with
the gem of an idea.

00:23:04.930 --> 00:23:08.440
But again, at the time
that "Amazing Race"

00:23:08.440 --> 00:23:10.150
was being pitched,
there were about four

00:23:10.150 --> 00:23:13.060
race-around-the-world-type
shows being pitched.

00:23:13.060 --> 00:23:16.570
And interestingly, I
was actually interviewed

00:23:16.570 --> 00:23:18.820
for another show that was--

00:23:18.820 --> 00:23:23.440
I think it was Fox Family,
which was later ABC Family.

00:23:23.440 --> 00:23:25.540
I was in for an
interview for that show

00:23:25.540 --> 00:23:28.030
when I heard about "The
Amazing Race" show.

00:23:28.030 --> 00:23:30.610
And they're working
title was, you

00:23:30.610 --> 00:23:33.510
know, "80 Days Around the
World" or whatever it was.

00:23:33.510 --> 00:23:37.690
And so they were pitching
them all at the same time.

00:23:37.690 --> 00:23:40.520
But again, the
idea is one thing.

00:23:40.520 --> 00:23:41.360
It's the execution.

00:23:41.360 --> 00:23:45.050
And so what I'm proud
of with "Amazing Race"

00:23:45.050 --> 00:23:47.750
is that I'm really proud
to be a part of a team that

00:23:47.750 --> 00:23:53.150
has continued to execute
this great idea very well

00:23:53.150 --> 00:23:56.107
and consistently for 17 years.

00:23:56.107 --> 00:23:58.190
CINDY HALVORSEN: So let's
talk about the logistics

00:23:58.190 --> 00:23:58.690
of the show.

00:23:58.690 --> 00:24:03.020
One of the things that really
amazed me when we set off in LA

00:24:03.020 --> 00:24:05.020
was just the production
value, right?

00:24:05.020 --> 00:24:06.840
So the number of people
traveling with us,

00:24:06.840 --> 00:24:09.530
the security, all the producers.

00:24:09.530 --> 00:24:12.020
What's one thing
that viewers would

00:24:12.020 --> 00:24:14.540
be really interested to know
from behind the scenes, other

00:24:14.540 --> 00:24:18.080
than you've mentioned a couple
times the 21 days of filming?

00:24:18.080 --> 00:24:21.590
PHIL KEOGHAN: Well, some
interesting information.

00:24:21.590 --> 00:24:24.890
For instance, every team has a
cameraman and a sound person.

00:24:24.890 --> 00:24:27.830
The team is never allowed
to leave that sound person.

00:24:27.830 --> 00:24:29.780
The sound person
and camera operator

00:24:29.780 --> 00:24:31.587
are completely independent.

00:24:31.587 --> 00:24:33.170
They have all the
batteries they need.

00:24:33.170 --> 00:24:36.560
They have all the tape
stock or recording device

00:24:36.560 --> 00:24:38.090
that they need.

00:24:38.090 --> 00:24:40.812
They really do operate
like an independent unit

00:24:40.812 --> 00:24:42.020
when they're with you, right?

00:24:42.020 --> 00:24:44.600
And there's quite
a bond that forms

00:24:44.600 --> 00:24:46.610
between the teams and the crew.

00:24:46.610 --> 00:24:49.070
Out of fairness, we do swap
up the crews and the teams

00:24:49.070 --> 00:24:53.990
so that one team doesn't always
have the same camera crew.

00:24:53.990 --> 00:24:56.560
When the teams
book their flights,

00:24:56.560 --> 00:24:58.310
they're booking for
four people, you know.

00:24:58.310 --> 00:25:02.690
There has to be room for
people to go onto the flight.

00:25:02.690 --> 00:25:05.270
Again, just the logistics
of 12 shows in 21 days.

00:25:05.270 --> 00:25:07.640
It's less than
two days per show.

00:25:07.640 --> 00:25:11.090
We want the teams
to be well fed,

00:25:11.090 --> 00:25:12.980
so we do feed them
at the pit stops.

00:25:12.980 --> 00:25:15.140
And you know, we want
them to be highly

00:25:15.140 --> 00:25:16.220
functioning human beings.

00:25:16.220 --> 00:25:17.000
CINDY HALVORSEN: Pit
stops were every two days.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:18.391
We were not well fed.

00:25:18.391 --> 00:25:19.266
PHIL KEOGHAN: Really?

00:25:19.266 --> 00:25:21.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:21.680 --> 00:25:22.340
Well, what--

00:25:22.340 --> 00:25:24.140
CINDY HALVORSEN: I,
like, really remember

00:25:24.140 --> 00:25:26.390
Jeremy eating someone's
hamburger from the airport

00:25:26.390 --> 00:25:27.020
cafeteria.

00:25:27.020 --> 00:25:28.220
He just stopped
someone and said,

00:25:28.220 --> 00:25:29.428
are you going to finish that?

00:25:29.428 --> 00:25:31.520
And he ate their burger.

00:25:31.520 --> 00:25:32.990
Because we were starving.

00:25:32.990 --> 00:25:33.890
PHIL KEOGHAN: The other
thing you should know

00:25:33.890 --> 00:25:36.080
is that "Amazing Race"
is a great diet plan.

00:25:36.080 --> 00:25:36.160
So--

00:25:36.160 --> 00:25:37.118
CINDY HALVORSEN: It is!

00:25:37.118 --> 00:25:38.660
Look how skinny I
was in the race.

00:25:38.660 --> 00:25:40.530
PHIL KEOGHAN: If you
want to lose weight,

00:25:40.530 --> 00:25:43.526
you can come in at 200
and you'll leave it 100.

00:25:43.526 --> 00:25:44.740
Yeah.

00:25:44.740 --> 00:25:45.240
Yeah.

00:25:45.240 --> 00:25:46.100
OK.

00:25:46.100 --> 00:25:48.560
Well, we try to feed them
really well at the pit stops.

00:25:48.560 --> 00:25:50.390
CINDY HALVORSEN: At the pit
stops, we get fed really well.

00:25:50.390 --> 00:25:50.510
PHIL KEOGHAN: Yeah.

00:25:50.510 --> 00:25:51.500
And then you get to sleep.

00:25:51.500 --> 00:25:52.220
CINDY HALVORSEN:
Stuff our pockets.

00:25:52.220 --> 00:25:52.700
PHIL KEOGHAN: Yeah.

00:25:52.700 --> 00:25:53.150
You get to sleep.

00:25:53.150 --> 00:25:54.410
CINDY HALVORSEN:
Like six hours before

00:25:54.410 --> 00:25:55.280
your next interview
has to start.

00:25:55.280 --> 00:25:55.988
PHIL KEOGHAN: OK.

00:25:55.988 --> 00:25:58.400
Well, we get to sleep
less than you, actually.

00:25:58.400 --> 00:25:59.900
CINDY HALVORSEN:
Oh, man, really?

00:25:59.900 --> 00:26:02.560
PHIL KEOGHAN: Oh, yeah, as
crew, I mean, yeah, absolutely.

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:05.570
So I always say that the
experience that you guys have

00:26:05.570 --> 00:26:07.970
is kind of like doing
interval training,

00:26:07.970 --> 00:26:11.000
where you sprint like crazy
and then you stop down

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:12.990
and then you sprint like
crazy and stop down.

00:26:12.990 --> 00:26:15.710
So for us, it's just nonstop.

00:26:15.710 --> 00:26:18.554
So only three teams go from
the beginning to the end.

00:26:18.554 --> 00:26:19.970
We as production,
obviously, we go

00:26:19.970 --> 00:26:21.594
from beginning to
end, the whole thing.

00:26:21.594 --> 00:26:25.340
And as soon as we're
finished with the teams,

00:26:25.340 --> 00:26:27.860
then we're already on to
trying to get to the next place

00:26:27.860 --> 00:26:29.690
to start shooting to stay ahead.

00:26:29.690 --> 00:26:32.510
And one of the reasons
that I started doing those

00:26:32.510 --> 00:26:35.420
live updates that I
do, which I wasn't

00:26:35.420 --> 00:26:37.512
doing when you were there.

00:26:37.512 --> 00:26:39.470
But one of the reasons
I started doing it was I

00:26:39.470 --> 00:26:42.260
was always just trying to
stay ahead of the teams

00:26:42.260 --> 00:26:43.430
to explain the challenges.

00:26:43.430 --> 00:26:45.710
So I had to go
everywhere they went.

00:26:45.710 --> 00:26:48.080
But a lot of times the
teams would turn up,

00:26:48.080 --> 00:26:50.908
and then I would have to
get out, get out of the way.

00:26:50.908 --> 00:26:52.407
So I was, like, so
frustrated that I

00:26:52.407 --> 00:26:56.234
was missing a lot of
explaining to the audience

00:26:56.234 --> 00:26:58.400
that I just said, all right,
just roll with the team

00:26:58.400 --> 00:26:59.930
running through
and I'll just say,

00:26:59.930 --> 00:27:02.185
you know, Ernie and Cindy
are the first to arrive

00:27:02.185 --> 00:27:02.810
at this detour.

00:27:02.810 --> 00:27:04.577
And what they have
to do is X, Y, and Z.

00:27:04.577 --> 00:27:06.410
So that's where those
live events came from.

00:27:06.410 --> 00:27:07.887
And then I had one shot to get--

00:27:07.887 --> 00:27:09.470
and the audience
loved the idea that I

00:27:09.470 --> 00:27:11.540
had one take to get it right.

00:27:11.540 --> 00:27:14.090
But you know, there
are times, I mean,

00:27:14.090 --> 00:27:16.280
in the history of
"Amazing Race" when

00:27:16.280 --> 00:27:19.610
the Globetrotters were on in
season 18, I think it was.

00:27:19.610 --> 00:27:21.070
We were in Prague.

00:27:21.070 --> 00:27:22.280
Was that-- no, it was 17.

00:27:22.280 --> 00:27:22.840
I'm sorry.

00:27:22.840 --> 00:27:23.990
We were in Prague.

00:27:23.990 --> 00:27:32.150
And I was there in Prague at
the pit stop for about 5 o'clock

00:27:32.150 --> 00:27:33.630
for the first team.

00:27:33.630 --> 00:27:36.500
I saw the sun set.

00:27:36.500 --> 00:27:38.810
I waited all night.

00:27:38.810 --> 00:27:41.480
I saw the sun rise,
and the Globetrotters

00:27:41.480 --> 00:27:45.830
arrived in the daylight
after I had been on a mat.

00:27:45.830 --> 00:27:49.160
And that was all we had was
a mat on a piece of grass

00:27:49.160 --> 00:27:51.530
out on the end of a
little island in Prague.

00:27:51.530 --> 00:27:54.170
And I was out there
for about 16 hours

00:27:54.170 --> 00:27:58.490
or whatever it was total to
wait for them to eliminate them.

00:27:58.490 --> 00:27:59.960
But that was not the record.

00:27:59.960 --> 00:28:04.190
The record was season 11
when I waited for the Guidos

00:28:04.190 --> 00:28:05.660
for 19 hours.

00:28:05.660 --> 00:28:09.430
I was at the pit stop
outside in the snow.

00:28:09.430 --> 00:28:11.970
CINDY HALVORSEN: You don't get
to go into a warm tent or van

00:28:11.970 --> 00:28:12.470
or--

00:28:12.470 --> 00:28:13.553
PHIL KEOGHAN: Not in-- no.

00:28:13.553 --> 00:28:17.120
There are some situations like
when we were in the Botswana--

00:28:17.120 --> 00:28:20.680
we were in the salt
pans in Africa.

00:28:20.680 --> 00:28:23.030
And there was no respite.

00:28:23.030 --> 00:28:25.710
The only respite you got
from the sun was an umbrella.

00:28:25.710 --> 00:28:27.860
And we were out there
for about 12 hours.

00:28:27.860 --> 00:28:29.120
So you get cooked.

00:28:29.120 --> 00:28:31.940
And there have been
times where I'm still

00:28:31.940 --> 00:28:34.210
waiting for the
last team to come in

00:28:34.210 --> 00:28:36.740
and the first team has gone
on to the next leg, which just

00:28:36.740 --> 00:28:38.310
throws everything into chaos.

00:28:38.310 --> 00:28:39.760
So we never shut down.

00:28:39.760 --> 00:28:41.510
Like this season, for
instance, is typical

00:28:41.510 --> 00:28:45.530
that we won't get to a hotel
for the first six, seven days.

00:28:45.530 --> 00:28:48.290
So this season, for
instance, I never got--

00:28:48.290 --> 00:28:51.950
we left Los Angeles, we
flew overnight to Panama,

00:28:51.950 --> 00:28:54.770
we shot all day, we flew
overnight to Brazil,

00:28:54.770 --> 00:28:57.320
we shot all day, we flew
overnight to Africa,

00:28:57.320 --> 00:28:58.890
we shot all day.

00:28:58.890 --> 00:29:01.700
And so we were up to
day six and we still

00:29:01.700 --> 00:29:04.190
hadn't been-- none of
us had been to a bed.

00:29:04.190 --> 00:29:06.800
So a lot of times I
get home and people

00:29:06.800 --> 00:29:09.515
say, Phil, you looked
like crap last night.

00:29:09.515 --> 00:29:10.140
I saw the show.

00:29:10.140 --> 00:29:13.060
You looked so bad.

00:29:13.060 --> 00:29:15.392
And I go, yeah, I know, I know.

00:29:15.392 --> 00:29:17.600
And they go, like, you looked
like just like a wreck.

00:29:17.600 --> 00:29:18.800
And I'm like, yeah.

00:29:18.800 --> 00:29:22.440
So of course, it's just me,
a cameraman, and a sound guy.

00:29:22.440 --> 00:29:24.980
I don't have a makeup person
or anyone looking after me.

00:29:24.980 --> 00:29:27.770
And occasionally the crew will
forget to tell me, you know,

00:29:27.770 --> 00:29:29.870
that my hair is sticking
up on some weird angle.

00:29:29.870 --> 00:29:32.840
And I wash my hair on the road
when I don't get to hotels.

00:29:32.840 --> 00:29:35.690
So I carry a little thing
of Johnson and Johnson

00:29:35.690 --> 00:29:39.570
shampoo, which is very
gentle on the scalp.

00:29:39.570 --> 00:29:41.460
I use that when I'm traveling.

00:29:41.460 --> 00:29:44.690
So I have crazy photographs
of me having my hair

00:29:44.690 --> 00:29:47.660
washed outside the Terracotta
Warriors in China, you know,

00:29:47.660 --> 00:29:50.000
or--

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:51.260
yeah.

00:29:51.260 --> 00:29:53.960
It's a really, really tough
gig, but it's a great gig.

00:29:53.960 --> 00:29:55.670
And it's a gig that
a lot of people, I

00:29:55.670 --> 00:29:57.211
don't know if they
really understand.

00:29:57.211 --> 00:30:00.440
Then I write the scripts with
one of the producers, Pat,

00:30:00.440 --> 00:30:01.490
before I leave.

00:30:01.490 --> 00:30:04.940
So then as we're going,
everything is changing.

00:30:04.940 --> 00:30:06.860
So I'm having to
write the scripts.

00:30:06.860 --> 00:30:09.526
So a lot of times I'm on a plane
and I just want to go to sleep,

00:30:09.526 --> 00:30:11.630
but I'm having to
rewrite scripts.

00:30:11.630 --> 00:30:13.850
Or the last show isn't
written before we take off,

00:30:13.850 --> 00:30:15.380
and then I'm
exhausted, and then I'm

00:30:15.380 --> 00:30:17.990
writing that on the last
flight in to the end city.

00:30:17.990 --> 00:30:20.610
Like what happened this time.

00:30:20.610 --> 00:30:23.270
So I'm not complaining, by
the way, because I love it.

00:30:23.270 --> 00:30:24.890
I'm just saying that
that is the gig.

00:30:24.890 --> 00:30:30.630
It's not 70 degrees
in an LA studio

00:30:30.630 --> 00:30:34.075
doing a show where people sing.

00:30:34.075 --> 00:30:36.450
CINDY HALVORSEN: So I shouldn't
complain about our eating

00:30:36.450 --> 00:30:38.620
every two days because
you didn't eat for six?

00:30:38.620 --> 00:30:40.620
PHIL KEOGHAN: No, because
it's-- no, no, no, no.

00:30:40.620 --> 00:30:41.520
I'm not saying--

00:30:41.520 --> 00:30:44.430
I'm not comparing it that way
because I think it's tough.

00:30:44.430 --> 00:30:46.050
I think it's just a tough gig.

00:30:46.050 --> 00:30:47.580
It's tough for the racers.

00:30:47.580 --> 00:30:50.520
It's way tougher
than people realize.

00:30:50.520 --> 00:30:53.730
But I also think that a
lot of people who are not--

00:30:53.730 --> 00:30:55.950
who haven't been out, they
don't understand just also

00:30:55.950 --> 00:30:57.240
how hard it is for the crew.

00:30:57.240 --> 00:30:59.823
I mean, you think about the crew
running around after you guys

00:30:59.823 --> 00:31:00.900
and what they do.

00:31:00.900 --> 00:31:01.650
It's pretty crazy.

00:31:01.650 --> 00:31:03.060
You getting a shot there, Ernie?

00:31:03.060 --> 00:31:03.809
ERNIE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:31:03.809 --> 00:31:05.180
PHIL KEOGHAN: Yeah, just--

00:31:05.180 --> 00:31:06.359
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:06.359 --> 00:31:06.900
There you go.

00:31:06.900 --> 00:31:07.470
All right.

00:31:07.470 --> 00:31:10.230
CINDY HALVORSEN: So if you
could host any other show,

00:31:10.230 --> 00:31:11.440
what show would you host?

00:31:11.440 --> 00:31:12.148
PHIL KEOGHAN: Uh.

00:31:14.590 --> 00:31:15.370
I like my show.

00:31:15.370 --> 00:31:16.480
I like this show I do.

00:31:16.480 --> 00:31:18.146
CINDY HALVORSEN: Not
even like the Emmys

00:31:18.146 --> 00:31:20.684
or "The Bachelor," all
your pretty ladies now?

00:31:20.684 --> 00:31:22.850
PHIL KEOGHAN: That's the
last show I'd want to host.

00:31:22.850 --> 00:31:24.010
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:24.010 --> 00:31:25.960
I find it so depressing.

00:31:25.960 --> 00:31:26.470
Oh, god.

00:31:26.470 --> 00:31:30.320
I just watch what some people
do and I just think, oh, no,

00:31:30.320 --> 00:31:31.000
please don't.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:31.830
Don't put that on.

00:31:31.830 --> 00:31:36.210
I find it-- like, I really
feel myself cringing for them.

00:31:36.210 --> 00:31:38.770
I'm just, oh, no, don't
do that, no, don't.

00:31:38.770 --> 00:31:43.300
No, I think maybe
shows that I really--

00:31:43.300 --> 00:31:46.330
reality shows that
I really like.

00:31:46.330 --> 00:31:49.990
I love-- has anybody seen
"Chef's Table" at all?

00:31:49.990 --> 00:31:52.720
Beautifully shot,
beautiful show.

00:31:52.720 --> 00:31:55.750
I love Anthony
Bourdain, you know.

00:31:55.750 --> 00:31:58.097
Some people, you
know, really love him.

00:31:58.097 --> 00:31:59.180
Some people don't get him.

00:31:59.180 --> 00:32:00.880
But I like him, and
I like that show.

00:32:00.880 --> 00:32:02.050
I find it fascinating.

00:32:02.050 --> 00:32:04.240
Ironically, every
time he does anything

00:32:04.240 --> 00:32:06.550
to do with food and
cooking, I can't watch.

00:32:06.550 --> 00:32:08.500
I don't like it
because my pet peeve

00:32:08.500 --> 00:32:10.679
is watching people eat on TV.

00:32:10.679 --> 00:32:12.220
CINDY HALVORSEN:
But you make us eat.

00:32:12.220 --> 00:32:13.820
Well, we didn't eat in
our season, thankfully.

00:32:13.820 --> 00:32:15.310
PHIL KEOGHAN: Well, that's
when it's a challenge.

00:32:15.310 --> 00:32:17.200
But the thing I hate
more than anything

00:32:17.200 --> 00:32:19.660
is when people eat on TV
and then they do the whole--

00:32:22.999 --> 00:32:24.057
oh, that's good.

00:32:24.057 --> 00:32:24.851
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:24.851 --> 00:32:25.811
It's like, no.

00:32:25.811 --> 00:32:27.310
And what I love
about "Chef's Table"

00:32:27.310 --> 00:32:28.726
is they don't--
if you look at it,

00:32:28.726 --> 00:32:30.820
they don't show people eating.

00:32:30.820 --> 00:32:34.240
It's all about the story behind
the food, behind the person,

00:32:34.240 --> 00:32:35.830
and the passion for the food.

00:32:35.830 --> 00:32:38.350
And they prepare the food
and they show the food,

00:32:38.350 --> 00:32:40.540
but they don't do the
gratuitous, like, people just

00:32:40.540 --> 00:32:41.530
eating food.

00:32:41.530 --> 00:32:44.200
So anyway, why am I
even talking about this?

00:32:44.200 --> 00:32:47.410
Because I would never be
able to do a show about food

00:32:47.410 --> 00:32:50.440
because I just love eating
food, not on camera.

00:32:50.440 --> 00:32:52.040
And I don't know how to cook.

00:32:52.040 --> 00:32:54.700
But I think those sort
of shows, I love that.

00:32:54.700 --> 00:32:57.050
I love-- you know, if you're
talking about nonfiction,

00:32:57.050 --> 00:32:59.860
I love any documentary.

00:32:59.860 --> 00:33:01.760
Really fascinated with
real-life stories.

00:33:01.760 --> 00:33:02.720
I love "60 Minutes."

00:33:02.720 --> 00:33:04.337
It's like my staple.

00:33:04.337 --> 00:33:06.670
If I was stuck on an island
and I had to watch one show,

00:33:06.670 --> 00:33:09.211
I'd probably watch that because
you're going to see Lady Gaga

00:33:09.211 --> 00:33:12.160
on one end and then you're going
to see some really heavy piece

00:33:12.160 --> 00:33:15.040
about really understanding
what's going on in Iraq

00:33:15.040 --> 00:33:16.690
or where they--
you're always seeing--

00:33:16.690 --> 00:33:19.711
I love-- I love real stuff.

00:33:19.711 --> 00:33:22.210
That's why I think I find it
hard to watch, like, "Bachelor"

00:33:22.210 --> 00:33:23.709
because it's just
like, oh, no, just

00:33:23.709 --> 00:33:26.020
go meet some people
in real life.

00:33:26.020 --> 00:33:27.640
Don't do that to yourself.

00:33:27.640 --> 00:33:28.180
It's OK.

00:33:28.180 --> 00:33:29.791
You don't need a rose.

00:33:29.791 --> 00:33:31.629
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:31.629 --> 00:33:33.670
CINDY HALVORSEN: Well,
speaking of documentaries,

00:33:33.670 --> 00:33:36.166
I do want to take a moment
to share the preview

00:33:36.166 --> 00:33:37.290
clip of your movie tonight.

00:33:37.290 --> 00:33:38.180
PHIL KEOGHAN: Oh, thank you.

00:33:38.180 --> 00:33:39.418
CINDY HALVORSEN: So
why don't we roll that?

00:33:39.418 --> 00:33:40.084
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:33:40.084 --> 00:33:42.382
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:33:42.382 --> 00:33:46.334
[CHEERING]

00:33:46.334 --> 00:33:48.804
[PANTING]

00:33:48.804 --> 00:33:51.768
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:34:05.650 --> 00:34:08.585
- This is a story about
courageous underdogs,

00:34:08.585 --> 00:34:10.960
the first English-speaking
team to compete in the Tour de

00:34:10.960 --> 00:34:11.949
France.

00:34:11.949 --> 00:34:15.340
I don't know why people want
to take on these challenges,

00:34:15.340 --> 00:34:17.139
but I really believe
that it's only

00:34:17.139 --> 00:34:20.980
by pushing yourself to
the borders of suffering

00:34:20.980 --> 00:34:24.340
and discomfort that you
really find out who you are.

00:34:24.340 --> 00:34:26.260
This is an insane idea.

00:34:26.260 --> 00:34:29.659
But what about if
you actually go back

00:34:29.659 --> 00:34:31.690
and you retrace every mile?

00:34:31.690 --> 00:34:36.170
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:34:36.170 --> 00:34:37.550
This is the dream team--

00:34:37.550 --> 00:34:40.320
my buddy Ben, highway
patrol officer Greg,

00:34:40.320 --> 00:34:41.760
and ace shooter Scott.

00:34:41.760 --> 00:34:44.340
- These races were meant to
be like the last man standing.

00:34:44.340 --> 00:34:46.881
- I don't think you know what
you're letting yourself in for.

00:34:46.881 --> 00:34:49.119
And if you did,
you wouldn't do it.

00:34:49.119 --> 00:34:52.610
- I'm going to try to make this
ride as authentic as I possibly

00:34:52.610 --> 00:34:53.370
can.

00:34:53.370 --> 00:34:56.261
My bike feels like
it's got a [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:56.261 --> 00:34:57.480
- It's not like that.

00:34:57.480 --> 00:34:59.000
You'll kill yourself.

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:01.790
[TRUCK HORN BLOWING]

00:35:01.790 --> 00:35:05.240
- To ride a 1928 bike
along the same roads

00:35:05.240 --> 00:35:07.520
while sticking to
the same schedule?

00:35:07.520 --> 00:35:08.720
Is that even possible?

00:35:08.720 --> 00:35:09.860
- This way or this way?

00:35:09.860 --> 00:35:10.956
- No, [SPEAKING FRENCH]

00:35:10.956 --> 00:35:11.580
- OK, this way?

00:35:11.580 --> 00:35:13.252
- Yes.

00:35:13.252 --> 00:35:14.090
- [SPEAKING FRENCH]

00:35:14.090 --> 00:35:15.020
- Are we going that way?

00:35:15.020 --> 00:35:15.540
- Yes.

00:35:15.540 --> 00:35:16.539
- OK, let's turn around.

00:35:16.539 --> 00:35:17.920
This way.

00:35:17.920 --> 00:35:20.370
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:35:24.290 --> 00:35:27.310
- Climbing 20,000
feet in one day.

00:35:27.310 --> 00:35:28.980
That's insane.

00:35:28.980 --> 00:35:33.550
There are huge stretches of
time that I don't remember.

00:35:33.550 --> 00:35:36.250
- Beyond bru-- brutal.

00:35:36.250 --> 00:35:37.928
Beyond brutal.

00:35:37.928 --> 00:35:40.844
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:35:48.290 --> 00:35:50.470
- Man, do I have some
respect for the riders who

00:35:50.470 --> 00:35:51.596
rode in 1928.

00:35:51.596 --> 00:35:54.464
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:36:00.210 --> 00:36:02.350
The most challenging
parts are yet to come.

00:36:02.350 --> 00:36:05.170
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:36:05.170 --> 00:36:06.009
[END PLAYBACK]

00:36:06.009 --> 00:36:07.050
CINDY HALVORSEN: Awesome.

00:36:07.050 --> 00:36:07.990
PHIL KEOGHAN: Yeah.

00:36:07.990 --> 00:36:08.810
It was a long ride.

00:36:08.810 --> 00:36:11.083
[APPLAUSE]

00:36:11.245 --> 00:36:13.620
CINDY HALVORSEN: So tell us
a little bit about the movie.

00:36:13.620 --> 00:36:16.320
Where did you get the
inspiration to do this movie?

00:36:16.320 --> 00:36:19.410
PHIL KEOGHAN: Well, I love
stories about underdogs.

00:36:19.410 --> 00:36:21.630
I think that's why I always
root for the underdogs

00:36:21.630 --> 00:36:22.880
on "Amazing Race."

00:36:22.880 --> 00:36:25.770
I just find-- it's
like the Cubs, right?

00:36:25.770 --> 00:36:29.430
It's like that story,
that story of people

00:36:29.430 --> 00:36:32.910
doing something that
is so well deserved

00:36:32.910 --> 00:36:34.300
after so much hard work.

00:36:34.300 --> 00:36:36.660
And I always read
books about underdogs,

00:36:36.660 --> 00:36:40.230
like the guy who came up with
the clock that could keep time

00:36:40.230 --> 00:36:42.630
for Captain Cook when he was
traveling over the oceans

00:36:42.630 --> 00:36:44.040
to be able to map the world out.

00:36:44.040 --> 00:36:47.220
They needed to have Greenwich
Mean Time on the ship,

00:36:47.220 --> 00:36:48.870
and they needed to
have a clock that

00:36:48.870 --> 00:36:52.260
would withstand the rigors
of being at sea on a ship.

00:36:52.260 --> 00:36:54.600
And this one guy who
was a carpenter, who

00:36:54.600 --> 00:36:57.360
wasn't a scientist,
spent his lifetime

00:36:57.360 --> 00:36:59.280
making five clocks
before he finally

00:36:59.280 --> 00:37:01.140
came up with a clock
that could keep time.

00:37:01.140 --> 00:37:02.940
And all the scientists couldn't
believe that a carpenter

00:37:02.940 --> 00:37:04.350
came up with the solution.

00:37:04.350 --> 00:37:07.157
So I always love those
kinds of stories.

00:37:07.157 --> 00:37:09.490
And I found a book about the
first English-speaking team

00:37:09.490 --> 00:37:11.310
to ride in the Tour
de France, which

00:37:11.310 --> 00:37:13.860
happened to be the tour
with the highest attrition

00:37:13.860 --> 00:37:17.000
rate of any tour in history.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:18.690
And I thought, wow.

00:37:18.690 --> 00:37:20.010
How do I not know this story?

00:37:20.010 --> 00:37:21.630
I love the Tour de France.

00:37:21.630 --> 00:37:22.680
I'm from New Zealand.

00:37:22.680 --> 00:37:25.680
There's one New Zealander
and three Australians.

00:37:25.680 --> 00:37:28.300
So I decided I would
tell the story,

00:37:28.300 --> 00:37:30.780
bring it to life somehow
in a documentary.

00:37:30.780 --> 00:37:32.730
And of course, all
those riders are

00:37:32.730 --> 00:37:34.980
all gone, and all the people
who remember those riders

00:37:34.980 --> 00:37:36.919
and remember that
time, they're all gone.

00:37:36.919 --> 00:37:38.460
And so I thought,
rather than telling

00:37:38.460 --> 00:37:40.590
the story in a traditional
documentary style

00:37:40.590 --> 00:37:42.410
where I would be on
the outside and show

00:37:42.410 --> 00:37:44.870
a bunch of archival
footage and tell the story,

00:37:44.870 --> 00:37:49.140
researching and being more
of a spectator, if you like.

00:37:49.140 --> 00:37:54.030
If I put myself in the story
and I rode a 1928 Tour de France

00:37:54.030 --> 00:37:56.100
bike that weighs twice
as much as a modern bike,

00:37:56.100 --> 00:37:59.130
that has no gears, I went
over every single road,

00:37:59.130 --> 00:38:00.990
I went to every--
over every single--

00:38:00.990 --> 00:38:03.049
to every single town and
over all the mountains,

00:38:03.049 --> 00:38:04.590
I could have a
different perspective.

00:38:04.590 --> 00:38:10.050
And we could juxtapose 1928 with
when we rode it in modern times

00:38:10.050 --> 00:38:12.610
and try to bring
the story to life.

00:38:12.610 --> 00:38:15.760
And it's one of the more
stupid things I've ever done,

00:38:15.760 --> 00:38:16.980
but it's--

00:38:16.980 --> 00:38:19.410
because you cannot
take on a physical--

00:38:19.410 --> 00:38:22.800
we were riding an average
of 150 miles a day.

00:38:22.800 --> 00:38:25.770
We had seven stages
over 200 miles.

00:38:25.770 --> 00:38:28.350
We had one day that took
us 23 and 1/2 hours.

00:38:28.350 --> 00:38:30.660
And the idea of trying to
take on a physical challenge

00:38:30.660 --> 00:38:37.120
like that while you're making a
movie is just not a good idea.

00:38:37.120 --> 00:38:41.710
However, I mentioned before
that I love technology.

00:38:41.710 --> 00:38:42.750
I love new technology.

00:38:42.750 --> 00:38:45.120
Sony heard that I was
going to do this--

00:38:45.120 --> 00:38:46.309
have a good friend at Sony--

00:38:46.309 --> 00:38:47.850
and they said,
listen, would you like

00:38:47.850 --> 00:38:52.590
to try out our brand-new F55
4K camera on your documentary?

00:38:52.590 --> 00:38:55.260
And no documentary had
ever been shot in 4K

00:38:55.260 --> 00:38:58.270
with an F55 camera
at that point.

00:38:58.270 --> 00:38:59.670
So I said, absolutely.

00:38:59.670 --> 00:39:02.010
And then Angenieux, which is
a French lens company that

00:39:02.010 --> 00:39:05.070
make beautiful
lenses, they loaned us

00:39:05.070 --> 00:39:09.227
$400,000 worth of beautiful
French fast lenses.

00:39:09.227 --> 00:39:11.310
Really, for any of you who
know about photography,

00:39:11.310 --> 00:39:14.130
super fast lenses that allow
you to shoot in really low light

00:39:14.130 --> 00:39:14.970
conditions.

00:39:14.970 --> 00:39:17.280
So we had this
incredible technology.

00:39:17.280 --> 00:39:18.600
And then one of our--

00:39:18.600 --> 00:39:21.109
one of my best friends who
I've known for 30 years, way

00:39:21.109 --> 00:39:22.650
before "Amazing
Race" but he ended up

00:39:22.650 --> 00:39:24.000
working on "Amazing Race"--

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:25.530
he's this incredible shooter.

00:39:25.530 --> 00:39:27.720
When I rode across America
to raise money for MS

00:39:27.720 --> 00:39:30.390
a few years ago, he sat
on a motorbike backwards

00:39:30.390 --> 00:39:32.231
for 3,500 miles.

00:39:32.231 --> 00:39:34.230
And I called him up and
I said, hey, Scott, I've

00:39:34.230 --> 00:39:35.657
got a great idea.

00:39:35.657 --> 00:39:36.990
We're going to go around France.

00:39:36.990 --> 00:39:39.000
We're going to retrace
the 1928 Tour de France.

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:40.624
How would you feel
about shooting that?

00:39:40.624 --> 00:39:42.887
And he goes, do I have to
sit on a motorbike backwards

00:39:42.887 --> 00:39:43.470
to shoot that?

00:39:43.470 --> 00:39:44.136
And I went, yes.

00:39:44.136 --> 00:39:46.274
And he went, OK, I'm in.

00:39:46.274 --> 00:39:47.940
So he's seen America
backwards, and he's

00:39:47.940 --> 00:39:50.280
seen all of France backwards.

00:39:50.280 --> 00:39:52.140
And so we shot this film.

00:39:52.140 --> 00:39:54.690
And we couldn't get funding
in the beginning for it,

00:39:54.690 --> 00:39:56.160
so it's all self-funded.

00:39:56.160 --> 00:39:58.260
It took five years to make.

00:39:58.260 --> 00:40:00.590
And the Google connection
here with the film,

00:40:00.590 --> 00:40:03.510
if you saw in the trailer where
we come zooming in out of space

00:40:03.510 --> 00:40:05.460
and we go into the
Arc de Triomphe

00:40:05.460 --> 00:40:06.870
and into the Champs-Elysees.

00:40:06.870 --> 00:40:10.410
So Craig Manning,
who works in your--

00:40:10.410 --> 00:40:12.510
worked for Google in
New York and now is

00:40:12.510 --> 00:40:16.150
working on another project
in conjunction with Google--

00:40:16.150 --> 00:40:16.930
I called him up.

00:40:16.930 --> 00:40:18.096
He's a fellow New Zealander.

00:40:18.096 --> 00:40:18.960
And I said, listen.

00:40:18.960 --> 00:40:21.660
I'm using Google right now
to retrace the 1928 Tour

00:40:21.660 --> 00:40:22.160
de France.

00:40:22.160 --> 00:40:25.920
And I'd love to use one
of your maps to, like,

00:40:25.920 --> 00:40:27.880
fly in to the Arc de Triomphe.

00:40:27.880 --> 00:40:28.816
Can you help me?

00:40:28.816 --> 00:40:30.690
So he hooked me up with
some guys in Boulder,

00:40:30.690 --> 00:40:32.520
where my daughter
is at university.

00:40:32.520 --> 00:40:35.730
So I went to the Google
office in Boulder.

00:40:35.730 --> 00:40:37.260
And I worked with a guy there.

00:40:37.260 --> 00:40:42.940
And then there's two maps in the
film that you'll actually see.

00:40:42.940 --> 00:40:46.410
And we rendered them all
to be able to match 4K

00:40:46.410 --> 00:40:48.600
so the quality is really good.

00:40:48.600 --> 00:40:51.030
The other Google connection
is, I decided that I really

00:40:51.030 --> 00:40:56.090
needed to have aerials of France
in order to bring this to life.

00:40:56.090 --> 00:40:59.670
And so I went on Google Maps
and I'm starting to, like,

00:40:59.670 --> 00:41:01.080
fly around on Google Maps.

00:41:01.080 --> 00:41:03.867
And what I realized was
that I could actually fly--

00:41:03.867 --> 00:41:05.700
because I didn't have
a whole bunch of money

00:41:05.700 --> 00:41:08.220
to spend on helicopter time--

00:41:08.220 --> 00:41:12.420
I could fly at a certain
speed from point A to point B

00:41:12.420 --> 00:41:16.057
and save KMZ files of
each of the plot points

00:41:16.057 --> 00:41:18.390
and work out where I wanted
to shoot the Col d'Aubisque.

00:41:18.390 --> 00:41:20.014
I wanted to be 500
feet off the ground.

00:41:20.014 --> 00:41:21.600
I want to be in
this position right

00:41:21.600 --> 00:41:23.725
here to get the mountains
at that level and the Col

00:41:23.725 --> 00:41:25.150
d'Aubisque and see the road.

00:41:25.150 --> 00:41:28.020
And so I saved all
these KMZ files.

00:41:28.020 --> 00:41:30.270
Then I gave all of those
files to the pilot.

00:41:30.270 --> 00:41:34.170
I said-- and then I made
a video of the route.

00:41:34.170 --> 00:41:36.930
And then I put it all
in electronic form,

00:41:36.930 --> 00:41:37.980
give it all to him.

00:41:37.980 --> 00:41:39.930
He pulled it up on his computer.

00:41:39.930 --> 00:41:42.360
We got the helicopter
out of Spain

00:41:42.360 --> 00:41:44.580
to fly across the
Pyrenees into France.

00:41:44.580 --> 00:41:47.326
And he literally just
followed the KMZ files

00:41:47.326 --> 00:41:48.450
that I made in Google Maps.

00:41:48.450 --> 00:41:49.675
And then he knew exactly--

00:41:49.675 --> 00:41:52.050
like, I didn't have to explain
to him, go a little lower.

00:41:52.050 --> 00:41:53.150
Go a little to the right.

00:41:53.150 --> 00:41:55.500
He had the exact spot.

00:41:55.500 --> 00:41:57.015
So I did all of
that in Google Maps

00:41:57.015 --> 00:41:58.890
before we got up in the
air and we're burning

00:41:58.890 --> 00:42:01.230
expensive helicopter fuel.

00:42:01.230 --> 00:42:03.630
So saved me a tremendous amount.

00:42:03.630 --> 00:42:06.180
And then just recently
I did a project

00:42:06.180 --> 00:42:08.400
for the Smithsonian
Channel, which

00:42:08.400 --> 00:42:12.750
is all aerials of New Zealand,
like, every single shot,

00:42:12.750 --> 00:42:16.330
an aerial shot of New Zealand.

00:42:16.330 --> 00:42:18.390
And I did exactly
the same thing.

00:42:18.390 --> 00:42:21.314
And I went and I was able to see
exactly where and how to do it.

00:42:21.314 --> 00:42:22.980
And it's all because
of that technology,

00:42:22.980 --> 00:42:25.901
which is such a great
tool now for filmmakers.

00:42:25.901 --> 00:42:27.150
CINDY HALVORSEN: That's great.

