IDRIES ABDUR-RAHMAN:
It was challenging.

00:47:20.175 --> 00:47:20.580
It was--

00:47:20.580 --> 00:47:21.840
PHIL KEOGHAN: But
when you filled out

00:47:21.840 --> 00:47:23.430
the form to come onto
the show, did they

00:47:23.430 --> 00:47:24.210
ask you if you could swim?

00:47:24.210 --> 00:47:24.280
IDRIES ABDUR-RAHMAN: They did.

00:47:24.280 --> 00:47:26.280
I can swim, but I'm
not a good swimmer.

00:47:26.280 --> 00:47:26.570
PHIL KEOGHAN: Right.

00:47:26.570 --> 00:47:27.580
IDRIES ABDUR-RAHMAN: When
they put you in the ocean,

00:47:27.580 --> 00:47:29.163
you're kind of like,
I'm going to die.

00:47:29.163 --> 00:47:30.210
PHIL KEOGHAN: Yeah.

00:47:30.210 --> 00:47:31.200
I get that.

00:47:31.200 --> 00:47:32.820
I mean, it's a fear
for some people.

00:47:32.820 --> 00:47:34.440
You know, they get in the ocean.

00:47:34.440 --> 00:47:36.273
I was just talking to
a guy who didn't learn

00:47:36.273 --> 00:47:37.630
how to swim until he was 36.

00:47:37.630 --> 00:47:39.630
And he said it was the
biggest thing in his life

00:47:39.630 --> 00:47:41.200
to try to learn how to do that.

00:47:41.200 --> 00:47:41.640
IDRIES ABDUR-RAHMAN: Yeah.

00:47:41.640 --> 00:47:43.263
It's still kind of a--
it's a big thing for me.

00:47:43.263 --> 00:47:44.880
I have my kids in swimming
because, you know, I'm like--

00:47:44.880 --> 00:47:47.250
PHIL KEOGHAN: You should
just keep going at it.

00:47:47.250 --> 00:47:47.850
IDRIES ABDUR-RAHMAN:
I'm going to.

00:47:47.850 --> 00:47:47.940
PHIL KEOGHAN: Don't give up.

00:47:47.940 --> 00:47:48.140
IDRIES ABDUR-RAHMAN:
I'm going to.

00:47:48.140 --> 00:47:49.320
PHIL KEOGHAN: Don't give up.

00:47:49.320 --> 00:47:50.070
What about you?

00:47:50.070 --> 00:47:51.790
KURT GIBSON: I think
arts and crafts.

00:47:51.790 --> 00:47:53.790
I know it sounds
silly, but we basically

00:47:53.790 --> 00:47:56.670
got eliminated because
we got towards the back

00:47:56.670 --> 00:47:58.800
when I had to tie those
little tiny, like, salt

00:47:58.800 --> 00:48:01.350
bags and my fingers couldn't
really get around it.

00:48:01.350 --> 00:48:04.282
And then Brodie building a
kite really put us far back.

00:48:04.282 --> 00:48:06.240
So if we could just kind
of build these things.

00:48:06.240 --> 00:48:06.840
PHIL KEOGHAN: But
you're not-- let's

00:48:06.840 --> 00:48:07.980
be honest-- you're
not going to go out

00:48:07.980 --> 00:48:09.834
and do macrame class,
you know what I mean?

00:48:09.834 --> 00:48:11.500
KURT GIBSON: Hey, for
a million dollars?

00:48:11.500 --> 00:48:12.510
PHIL KEOGHAN: No,
but I mean now.

00:48:12.510 --> 00:48:14.160
It's not like you're
rushing out to go do--

00:48:14.160 --> 00:48:15.060
KURT GIBSON: Oh, no, now, no.

00:48:15.060 --> 00:48:15.610
No.

00:48:15.610 --> 00:48:16.180
PHIL KEOGHAN: You're
not doing arts and--

00:48:16.180 --> 00:48:16.800
KURT GIBSON: No, no, no.

00:48:16.800 --> 00:48:17.670
PHIL KEOGHAN: With
you, anything?

00:48:17.670 --> 00:48:18.330
Was there--

00:48:18.330 --> 00:48:20.080
CINDY HALVORSEN: I
think the only thing is

00:48:20.080 --> 00:48:21.600
I wish I was a little taller.

00:48:21.600 --> 00:48:22.710
PHIL KEOGHAN: How
would that have helped?

00:48:22.710 --> 00:48:24.230
CINDY HALVORSEN: Everyone
was so tall in the race

00:48:24.230 --> 00:48:26.640
and they could run faster
because their legs were longer.

00:48:26.640 --> 00:48:28.181
They could climb
those ladders faster

00:48:28.181 --> 00:48:30.016
because their arms were longer.

00:48:30.016 --> 00:48:31.140
It really was an inhibitor.

00:48:31.140 --> 00:48:31.270
PHIL KEOGHAN: Do
you think we should

00:48:31.270 --> 00:48:33.380
standardize the height
for all the amazing races

00:48:33.380 --> 00:48:34.894
to make it fair?

00:48:34.894 --> 00:48:35.730
CINDY HALVORSEN: Hm.

00:48:35.730 --> 00:48:36.240
It might be a good one.

00:48:36.240 --> 00:48:37.020
PHIL KEOGHAN: But you won.

00:48:37.020 --> 00:48:37.380
ERNIE HALVORSEN: Right?

00:48:37.380 --> 00:48:37.963
She still won.

00:48:37.963 --> 00:48:39.601
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:40.007 --> 00:48:42.090
PHIL KEOGHAN: The tall
people are probably saying,

00:48:42.090 --> 00:48:44.370
you know, I wish I was shorter.

00:48:44.370 --> 00:48:47.259
All right, what surprised you
most once you were on the show?

00:48:47.259 --> 00:48:49.550
Like, what was the one thing
that really surprised you?

00:48:49.550 --> 00:48:50.841
CINDY HALVORSEN: The logistics.

00:48:50.841 --> 00:48:53.880
I feel like the moment we hit
that first mat and everything

00:48:53.880 --> 00:48:54.600
just popped up.

00:48:54.600 --> 00:48:56.820
It was like bounce
boards, cameras.

00:48:56.820 --> 00:48:58.350
Everyone scooped on in.

00:48:58.350 --> 00:48:59.351
That was really amazing.

00:48:59.351 --> 00:49:00.183
PHIL KEOGHAN: Right.

00:49:00.183 --> 00:49:02.220
But the stuff you don't
see behind the cameras.

00:49:02.220 --> 00:49:03.880
Was there something
that surprised you?

00:49:03.880 --> 00:49:04.920
IDRIES ABDUR-RAHMAN:
For me, it was the pace.

00:49:04.920 --> 00:49:06.755
I mean, you know, it
was just going so fast.

00:49:06.755 --> 00:49:07.080
PHIL KEOGHAN: It's relentless.

00:49:07.080 --> 00:49:08.621
IDRIES ABDUR-RAHMAN:
Just relentless.

00:49:08.621 --> 00:49:09.940
I was like, wow, this is crazy.

00:49:09.940 --> 00:49:11.815
ERNIE HALVORSEN: Yeah,
it was definitely more

00:49:11.815 --> 00:49:14.060
about the production,
going out there and just--

00:49:14.060 --> 00:49:15.420
you were just left on your own.

00:49:15.420 --> 00:49:17.461
Like, I thought there was
going to be more, like,

00:49:17.461 --> 00:49:18.110
scripted stuff.

00:49:18.110 --> 00:49:19.710
There's going to be more like,
here's what you're going to do.

00:49:19.710 --> 00:49:20.190
Blah, blah, blah.

00:49:20.190 --> 00:49:21.190
PHIL KEOGHAN: All right.

00:49:21.190 --> 00:49:22.820
Here's a great dramatic moment.

00:49:22.820 --> 00:49:23.820
What I want you to see--

00:49:23.820 --> 00:49:24.420
ERNIE HALVORSEN:
They just drop you!

00:49:24.420 --> 00:49:25.885
And I'm like, OK,
what do I do now?

00:49:25.885 --> 00:49:26.760
Cindy, what do we do?

00:49:26.760 --> 00:49:28.140
PHIL KEOGHAN: You guys
have all been on the show.

00:49:28.140 --> 00:49:30.840
And you will attest to the fact
that we really pride ourselves

00:49:30.840 --> 00:49:34.800
in trying to make the race
as authentic as possible.

00:49:34.800 --> 00:49:37.440
You hear people say,
oh, was that fake?

00:49:37.440 --> 00:49:38.370
Was that scripted?

00:49:38.370 --> 00:49:40.090
Was that set up and whatever?

00:49:40.090 --> 00:49:40.680
No.

00:49:40.680 --> 00:49:45.660
And we pride ourselves in,
you guys are like our writers.

00:49:45.660 --> 00:49:47.970
You write the content,
meaning whatever you do

00:49:47.970 --> 00:49:50.550
becomes the script, the
transcript of the show, right?

00:49:50.550 --> 00:49:53.250
So we set up the circumstances,
and we throw you out there

00:49:53.250 --> 00:49:54.390
to go do it.

00:49:54.390 --> 00:49:56.550
And how you react
to that stimulus

00:49:56.550 --> 00:49:58.187
is what creates the show.

00:49:58.187 --> 00:50:00.270
ERNIE HALVORSEN: I just
wasn't expecting that, so.

00:50:00.270 --> 00:50:02.080
PHIL KEOGHAN: You
know there are shows--

00:50:02.080 --> 00:50:05.790
there are shows that do
manipulate and, like,

00:50:05.790 --> 00:50:06.390
you know--

00:50:06.390 --> 00:50:08.490
we really pride
ourselves in trying

00:50:08.490 --> 00:50:12.000
to make a fair race as
much as possible, you know?

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:16.590
And man, one of the things I get
the most from fans is they'll

00:50:16.590 --> 00:50:19.507
say, why didn't you say
something to that teen?

00:50:19.507 --> 00:50:21.840
Like when the Twinnies moved
the money, do you remember?

00:50:21.840 --> 00:50:22.360
IDRIES ABDUR-RAHMAN: Um-hm.

00:50:22.360 --> 00:50:23.910
PHIL KEOGHAN: And there was
a season where the Twinnies--

00:50:23.910 --> 00:50:24.400
CINDY HALVORSEN: Oh, yeah.

00:50:24.400 --> 00:50:26.230
PHIL KEOGHAN: And I didn't know.

00:50:26.230 --> 00:50:29.710
Like, I don't see in real time
what the audience is seeing.

00:50:29.710 --> 00:50:32.734
But they see this happen,
and then they see me.

00:50:32.734 --> 00:50:34.900
And they think that somehow
I'm meant to know, like,

00:50:34.900 --> 00:50:36.100
every little detail.

00:50:36.100 --> 00:50:36.850
I haven't seen it.

00:50:36.850 --> 00:50:38.750
It's all just raw
footage at that point.

00:50:38.750 --> 00:50:40.750
So it's always, I have
to explain to them, well,

00:50:40.750 --> 00:50:41.770
hold on a second.

00:50:41.770 --> 00:50:45.070
At the point when I was
talking to them, first of all,

00:50:45.070 --> 00:50:45.730
I didn't know.

00:50:45.730 --> 00:50:48.880
But you've seen way more about
what just happened on that leg

00:50:48.880 --> 00:50:49.964
than I have at that point.

00:50:49.964 --> 00:50:50.921
ERNIE HALVORSEN: Right.

00:50:50.921 --> 00:50:53.080
PHIL KEOGHAN: Like later,
yeah, I catch up but--

00:50:53.080 --> 00:50:54.760
KURT GIBSON: I think that's part
of what makes the show so fun

00:50:54.760 --> 00:50:57.640
to watch too is, I mean, one
of our episodes in Chamonix,

00:50:57.640 --> 00:51:01.300
our favorite, we had to go zip
line to get that first clue.

00:51:01.300 --> 00:51:03.932
And so it's not really,
like, clear directions,

00:51:03.932 --> 00:51:06.140
but they're kind of like,
hey, you got to go do that.

00:51:06.140 --> 00:51:09.130
So Brodie starts going over
the ledge to go get hooked up.

00:51:09.130 --> 00:51:11.330
And he's like, all right,
what do I need to do?

00:51:11.330 --> 00:51:12.621
And the guy's like, no, no, no.

00:51:12.621 --> 00:51:13.300
Just one of you.

00:51:13.300 --> 00:51:16.676
And so Brodie kind of like looks
and is like, Kurt, you do this.

00:51:16.676 --> 00:51:17.800
I'm going back over, right?

00:51:17.800 --> 00:51:18.820
So it's just like,
we're dreading

00:51:18.820 --> 00:51:19.650
that moment, like, wait.

00:51:19.650 --> 00:51:20.350
I don't want to do that.

00:51:20.350 --> 00:51:21.266
You do that, you know?

00:51:21.266 --> 00:51:23.540
But just those kind of
moments make it fun.

00:51:23.540 --> 00:51:24.080
ERNIE HALVORSEN: The vagueness.

00:51:24.080 --> 00:51:24.880
You're like, you're
not sure if you're

00:51:24.880 --> 00:51:26.150
doing the right thing exactly.

00:51:26.150 --> 00:51:26.800
You're like, is this--

00:51:26.800 --> 00:51:29.133
PHIL KEOGHAN: But when you
think about the circumstances

00:51:29.133 --> 00:51:33.490
that you guys all end up in,
right, it takes a while when

00:51:33.490 --> 00:51:37.990
you get back to kind of process,
oh, my god, we were in Chamonix

00:51:37.990 --> 00:51:40.840
and we were about to
leap off a mountain.

00:51:40.840 --> 00:51:46.150
And it all, for me, it
takes me about two weeks

00:51:46.150 --> 00:51:48.280
to, like, process
everything that's happened.

00:51:48.280 --> 00:51:51.280
Because it's all happening
so fast and there's so much.

00:51:51.280 --> 00:51:52.072
So much so quickly.

00:51:52.072 --> 00:51:53.821
KURT GIBSON: And even
in the downtime too,

00:51:53.821 --> 00:51:55.550
you're like thinking
about the next leg.

00:51:55.550 --> 00:51:58.154
You're just like,
downtime, but you're

00:51:58.154 --> 00:52:00.070
getting ready to stress
for the next 24 hours.

00:52:00.070 --> 00:52:01.180
PHIL KEOGHAN: And then
we're interviewing

00:52:01.180 --> 00:52:02.254
you guys and [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:02.254 --> 00:52:03.670
CINDY HALVORSEN:
Well, and we tore

00:52:03.670 --> 00:52:05.770
through every hotel room
looking for any clue

00:52:05.770 --> 00:52:06.760
about the next day.

00:52:06.760 --> 00:52:07.730
PHIL KEOGHAN: Really?

00:52:07.730 --> 00:52:08.450
CINDY HALVORSEN: Yeah,
we showed up one day.

00:52:08.450 --> 00:52:09.635
ERNIE HALVORSEN: You guys pulled
the TVs out of every room.

00:52:09.635 --> 00:52:10.420
CINDY HALVORSEN: Yeah.

00:52:10.420 --> 00:52:12.190
Did you know that, the
TVs are not in the rooms?

00:52:12.190 --> 00:52:13.070
PHIL KEOGHAN: Yeah,
no, I know that.

00:52:13.070 --> 00:52:14.755
But you went with four TVs?

00:52:14.755 --> 00:52:15.420
ERNIE HALVORSEN: You
did that on purpose.

00:52:15.420 --> 00:52:16.230
CINDY HALVORSEN: No, we were
looking for any information.

00:52:16.230 --> 00:52:16.950
ERNIE HALVORSEN: They
were all in Phil's room.

00:52:16.950 --> 00:52:18.430
PHIL KEOGHAN: Don't make me
take that million dollars

00:52:18.430 --> 00:52:19.800
back when you tell me--

00:52:19.800 --> 00:52:20.720
CINDY HALVORSEN: We
didn't break any rules.

00:52:20.720 --> 00:52:22.610
PHIL KEOGHAN: I mean, that's
going to disqualify you.

00:52:22.610 --> 00:52:24.070
CINDY HALVORSEN: We
didn't break any rules.

00:52:24.070 --> 00:52:26.028
PHIL KEOGHAN: We had this
question come up here

00:52:26.028 --> 00:52:27.450
like that.

00:52:27.450 --> 00:52:29.860
CINDY HALVORSEN: OK, so this
is an audience question.

00:52:29.860 --> 00:52:31.521
What's the scariest
moment for you

00:52:31.521 --> 00:52:32.770
in "The Amazing Race" history?

00:52:32.770 --> 00:52:33.730
PHIL KEOGHAN: Is this
from somebody here,

00:52:33.730 --> 00:52:34.880
or is that someone--

00:52:34.880 --> 00:52:36.550
you could just talk to me.

00:52:36.550 --> 00:52:38.030
KURT GIBSON: Wow,
this is awesome.

00:52:38.030 --> 00:52:40.390
PHIL KEOGHAN: I mean, come on.

00:52:40.390 --> 00:52:42.609
I love technology, but,
dude, you can talk to me.

00:52:42.609 --> 00:52:43.692
CHARLES: No, I'm happy to.

00:52:43.692 --> 00:52:44.080
Yeah, [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:44.080 --> 00:52:44.530
PHIL KEOGHAN: Yeah,
what's our name?

00:52:44.530 --> 00:52:45.450
KURT GIBSON: No,
that was awesome.

00:52:45.450 --> 00:52:46.366
PHIL KEOGHAN: Charles.

00:52:46.366 --> 00:52:48.580
OK, Charles is in
the audience here.

00:52:48.580 --> 00:52:50.507
Charles, I love how
you use technology.

00:52:50.507 --> 00:52:52.840
CHARLES: I didn't know how
crowded it would get in here.

00:52:52.840 --> 00:52:53.140
PHIL KEOGHAN: OK.

00:52:53.140 --> 00:52:55.223
So you're saying, yeah,
what's the scariest moment

00:52:55.223 --> 00:52:56.691
in "The Amazing Race" history?

00:52:56.691 --> 00:52:58.440
CHARLES: Yeah, mine
was the watermelon one

00:52:58.440 --> 00:52:59.164
that you talked about.

00:52:59.164 --> 00:53:01.705
But I don't know if there was
any other ones that you thought

00:53:01.705 --> 00:53:03.910
were, like, pretty terrible.

00:53:03.910 --> 00:53:07.060
PHIL KEOGHAN: You know, I think
a lot of what the teams do

00:53:07.060 --> 00:53:10.420
is perceived danger, you know.

00:53:10.420 --> 00:53:11.860
All the challenges that they do.

00:53:11.860 --> 00:53:15.100
We're so ridiculous
about making sure

00:53:15.100 --> 00:53:19.970
that they're run stringently
and that the teams are safe.

00:53:19.970 --> 00:53:22.420
The part I worry about
the most is when a car--

00:53:22.420 --> 00:53:26.020
they get in a car, in a taxi,
and the car is driving fast.

00:53:26.020 --> 00:53:29.710
And maybe the teams ask
the driver to slow down.

00:53:29.710 --> 00:53:31.994
We've had cars, accidents
on the show before.

00:53:31.994 --> 00:53:33.910
And those are the calls
you don't want to get.

00:53:33.910 --> 00:53:36.130
When you get a call
and we find out a team

00:53:36.130 --> 00:53:38.830
has been in an accident.

00:53:38.830 --> 00:53:41.260
And Chip and Reichen
rolled a car in season 4.

00:53:41.260 --> 00:53:44.550
In season 1 we had
a team go over.

00:53:44.550 --> 00:53:46.300
I'm trying to think
of who was in the car.

00:53:46.300 --> 00:53:48.050
I think it was the
Guidos might have been.

00:53:48.050 --> 00:53:49.990
There was an accident.

00:53:49.990 --> 00:53:52.980
So yeah, that's the
scariest thing for me.

00:53:52.980 --> 00:53:56.260
I worry about them the
most when, like you said,

00:53:56.260 --> 00:53:57.910
when you guys are on your own.

00:53:57.910 --> 00:54:00.070
Even little things like
just crossing the road.

00:54:00.070 --> 00:54:02.410
Like, sometimes they'll
be in a crazy place,

00:54:02.410 --> 00:54:04.572
they might be in
India, and they're

00:54:04.572 --> 00:54:06.280
in a really busy
intersection, and that's

00:54:06.280 --> 00:54:07.363
where things can go wrong.

00:54:07.363 --> 00:54:10.720
Because they're out of
our control, you know.

00:54:10.720 --> 00:54:12.490
And that's the
part I worry about.

00:54:12.490 --> 00:54:14.940
For me, personal
scary moment was--

00:54:14.940 --> 00:54:18.330
not scary, but kind of surreal
moment-- was I was in Ukraine

00:54:18.330 --> 00:54:20.080
and we flew in in the
middle of the night.

00:54:20.080 --> 00:54:22.390
And I had a New
Zealand passport.

00:54:22.390 --> 00:54:25.752
And I was told I
didn't need a visa,

00:54:25.752 --> 00:54:28.210
but for whatever reason this
guy thought I did need a visa.

00:54:28.210 --> 00:54:30.280
So I was separated
from everybody.

00:54:30.280 --> 00:54:31.960
And the crew-- the
teams, sorry, were

00:54:31.960 --> 00:54:33.543
going to be arriving
the next morning,

00:54:33.543 --> 00:54:35.729
so I had a little bit
of a head start on them.

00:54:35.729 --> 00:54:37.270
So I was going to
be getting up early

00:54:37.270 --> 00:54:39.850
to go shoot all the
introductions to the challenges

00:54:39.850 --> 00:54:40.900
before the teams came in.

00:54:40.900 --> 00:54:42.400
And we were expecting
the first team

00:54:42.400 --> 00:54:44.620
to arrive at the mat at
10 o'clock in the morning.

00:54:44.620 --> 00:54:46.690
That was the estimated time.

00:54:46.690 --> 00:54:49.760
And anyway, they pulled me away.

00:54:49.760 --> 00:54:52.090
It was 1 o'clock
something in the morning.

00:54:52.090 --> 00:54:55.611
And they took me to this little
room and then left me there.

00:54:55.611 --> 00:54:56.860
And they didn't speak English.

00:54:56.860 --> 00:54:59.500
And I was like, OK.

00:54:59.500 --> 00:55:01.540
So I waited there
and waited there.

00:55:01.540 --> 00:55:04.300
And I had a sense that there was
something going on in the room

00:55:04.300 --> 00:55:05.370
